ltures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n		    Introduction \r\n \r\n	This set of role-playing rules is based on the d20 system  and 3.5E D&amp;D ,\r\n	with some additional inspiration from other d20 systems as well as 4E D&amp;D .\r\n	The RoL rules have been designed to be simpler and more flexible, but\r\n	also more realistic, than the original rules. However, the set of\r\n	classes, character races, monsters, spells, and so forth are basically\r\n	the same, and the new rules try to remain faithful to the cinematic and\r\n	high-fantasy feel of traditional D&amp;D.\r\n \r\n\r\nMotivation \r\n There are a whole lot of reasons behind the design of these rather\r\n	extensive &quot;house rules&quot;. First, let me say that I really like the\r\n	regular d20 and D&amp;D rules; they are clear, consistent, and fairly\r\n	simple compared to most of the older RPG systems I have had the\r\n	privilege of playing. Still, I felt that the rules could be made even\r\n	simpler and more generic, and I also felt that many of the rules could\r\n	be made more realistic without making them more complicated or less\r\n	entertaining. In total, there are quite a few d20 rules that I\'m not\r\n	satisfied with, many of which are actually a legacy from previous\r\n	versions of D&amp;D. Here are some examples: \r\n \r\n	 The concepts of spell slots and spell memorization never really\r\n		appealed to me. What is the logic in having a wizard that can cast a\r\n		level 5 spell but not a level 1 spell, just because he has already\r\n		used up all of his level 1 spell slots for the day and &quot;lost&quot; them\r\n		from memory? I greatly prefer a system that uses some sort of power\r\n		points. I also wanted to avoid the long preparation times where spell\r\n		casters have to decide which spells to memorize for the day, while the\r\n		other players just sit around and wait. \r\n	 I wanted a system where skills play a greater part for all\r\n		characters, not just for rogues and bards. By changing most of the\r\n		feats and class abilities into skills, I feel that I get a more\r\n		flexible and realistic system. Furthermore, I got rid of some really\r\n		uninteresting but nearly mandatory feats, such as Weapon Focus, Spell\r\n		Focus, and Combat Casting, by turning them into benefits granted by\r\n		skills. \r\n	 Also, turning feats and class abilities into skills makes it\r\n		possible for characters to choose how much or how little to specialize\r\n		in each ability, and they can specialize without having to switch to\r\n		odd prestige classes. \r\n	 Another benefit is that the stacking of abilities between different\r\n		classes becomes more logical when that ability is based on a skill\r\n		shared between the classes. Even spell casters can now multi-class\r\n		without necessarily sacrificing their ability to cast higher level\r\n		spells (as long as the two classes share some of their supernatural\r\n		skills). \r\n	 I\'ve wondered why characters should get better only at attacking\r\n		when increasing their level, while very few classes get better at\r\n		defending themselves. So, I\'ve changed the old Base Attack Bonus into\r\n		a much more generic system that can be used for defense as well as\r\n		offense. Also, increasing one\'s weapon skill will provide bonuses to\r\n		parrying as well as attacking. \r\n	 I never liked the concept of armor making a character harder to hit\r\n		rather than soaking up some of the impact, so I have changed the armor\r\n		system to provide the wearer with Damage Reduction instead. \r\n	 I wanted to reduce the relatively easy access to resurrection\r\n		magic. I prefer the concept of fate points or hero points that is used\r\n		in many other systems to avoid a high frequency of character death. \r\n \r\n\r\nMain Changes and Features \r\n This is a summary of the most important changes in these rules\r\n	compared to traditional 3.5E D&amp;D: \r\n \r\n	 The core rules have been made more streamlined, consistent, and\r\n		generic, with regards to d20\r\n			checks , modifiers , and\r\n		descriptors . \r\n	 The rules are based on a more distinct definition of core characteristics  and\r\n		their dependencies . \r\n	 The old saving throws have been replaced with passive defense scores  (very\r\n		similar to D&amp;D 4E). \r\n	 A set of social scores \r\n		(social class, wealth class, influence, and reputation) has been\r\n		added. \r\n	 The old level-based ability bonuses have been replaced with a more\r\n		generic improvement point \r\n		system. \r\n	 Fate points  have been\r\n		introduced to reduce the importance of resurrection magic. \r\n	 Open-ended d20 checks  are\r\n		used for all skill checks, attack rolls, etc. \r\n	 Most racial traits, class traits, and feats have been changed into\r\n		skills . \r\n	 Racial traits have been separated into racial and cultural traits. \r\n	 Some races have been changed into templates. \r\n	 The Barbarian class has been changed into a set of skills available to the\r\n		Fighter class. \r\n	 The Paladin and Blackguard classes have been changed into a more generic\r\n		Templar class. \r\n	 Skills have been divided into skill benefits  and skill actions . \r\n	 A system based on action\r\n			points  (increasing with level) has replaced all the old action\r\n		types. \r\n	 The size of a weapon affects attack speed. Larger weapons are slower but\r\n		can provide attacks of opportunity against opponents with smaller weapons. \r\n	 Both natural armor and manufactured armor now provide damage\r\n		resistance (instead of making the target harder to hit). \r\n	 Weapons and shields provide a parry bonus based on weapon and\r\n		skill. \r\n	 Low-level magic items have been replaced with additional levels of\r\n		high quality equipment. \r\n	 Spells and most supernatural abilities are now powered either by\r\n		physical or mental stamina (represented by stamina points and power\r\n		points, respectively). \r\n	 Spells have variable parameters and options instead of a fixed\r\n		effect and spell level. \r\n	 Spells make use of opposed checks and opposed power levels much\r\n		more than before. \r\n	 The creation of magic items has been made more streamlined. \r\n	 Residuum  (from D&amp;D 4E)\r\n		has been adopted as an alternative to spending XP on creating magic\r\n		items. \r\n	 Most costs, prices, treasures, etc. have been changed one\r\n		magnitude, from gold pieces to silver. \r\n \r\n		     \r\n         \r\n\r\n		\r\n         \r\n        \r\n            \r\n          \r\n		\r\n     \r\n \r\n ','2013-01-26',12.97,'a8a1afd6d00cc9e011cd92ba64f1561d',0,1),(72,2,'http://localhost/rold20/hb02_coremech.php','RoL d20 - Core Mechanics','','\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n	\r\n\r\n		\r\n	            \r\n	             \r\n	            \r\n	                 \r\n	                    RoL d20 Role-Playing System\r\n	                 \r\n	             \r\n			  \r\n		\r\n        \r\n			\r\n		 Handbook \r\n         \r\n             Introduction  \r\n             Core Mechanics  \r\n             \r\n                 Characteristics  \r\n                 Action Checks  \r\n                 Modifiers  \r\n                 Descriptors  \r\n                 Prerequisites  \r\n                 Conditions  \r\n                 Special Senses  \r\n                 Special Abilities  \r\n             \r\n             Character Generation  \r\n             \r\n                 Ability Scores  \r\n                 Character Races  \r\n                 Character Classes  \r\n                 Other Characteristics  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Combat  \r\n             \r\n                 Combat Sequence  \r\n                 Action Points  \r\n                 Combat Modifiers  \r\n                 Attack Types  \r\n                 Damage Types  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Magic  \r\n             \r\n                 Casting Spells  \r\n                 Learning Spells  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Environment  \r\n             \r\n                 Movement  \r\n                 Environment  \r\n                 The Multiverse  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Culture  \r\n             Rules of Engagement  \r\n             \r\n                 Encounters  \r\n                 Experience  \r\n                 Treasure  \r\n             \r\n             List of Skills  \r\n             \r\n                 Skill Availability  \r\n                 Skill Descriptions  \r\n             \r\n             List of Actions  \r\n             List of Spells  \r\n             List of Equipment  \r\n             \r\n	             Mundane Items  \r\n	             Complex Items  \r\n	             Item Modifications  \r\n	             Materials  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Creatures  \r\n             \r\n	             Aberrations  \r\n	             Animals  \r\n	             Monstrous Animals  \r\n	             Constructs  \r\n	             Dragons  \r\n	             Elementals  \r\n	             Humanoids  \r\n	             Monstrous Humanoids  \r\n	             Outsiders  \r\n	             Plants &amp; Fungi  \r\n	             Undead  \r\n	             Templates  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Cultures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Core Mechanics \r\n     \r\n    The RoL d20 rules are quite extensive and replace a large portion of the normal d20 and D&amp;D 3.5E rules. \r\n    Nevertheless, for the few areas not covered by this document, the regular \r\n    d20 rules  \r\n    still apply.\r\n    But don\'t forget... The DM is always right and can override any rule, even the RoL rules.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The main purpose of rules in a role-playing game is to provide a common framework for the players (and the DM).\r\n    First of all, it defines a set of characteristics that are used to describe player characters, non-player characters,\r\n    monsters, and even inanimate objects. For example, they let you know how strong, quick, or intelligent your character is,\r\n    in absolute numbers. In other words, it is easy to tell whether your character is stronger than an average orc or smarter\r\n    than the village wizard. Second, the rules define which actions your character can perform, your chances of success or\r\n    failure, and how long those actions take to perform. Of course, the rules cannot cover every possible action, so it is\r\n    the duty of the DM to adjudicate the cases not already covered by the rules.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Mathematics \r\n     \r\n     Dice:  The traditional role-playing notation for dice is used in the RoL rules.\r\n    In other words, &quot;3d6+5&quot; means &quot;roll three six-sided dice, calculate their sum, and add five&quot;.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Units:  Measurements in this document are given in metric units.\r\n    However, to avoid major confusion with D&amp;D, most distances, areas, and volumes are measured in squares.\r\n    The size of one square (or more accurately one of its edges) is equal to 5 feet or 1.5 m.\r\n    One square is also the appropriate spacing for a man-sized creature in combat situations.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For diagonal movement and measurements of distance, every other square (starting with the second one) counts double.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Rounding:  Unless otherwise specified, always round fractions down.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Multiplication:  When applying a single multiplier to a die roll or number, just multiply normally.\r\n    In some rare cases, such as a spell multiplying a weapon\'s damage combined with a critical hit,\r\n    several multiplicative modifiers will apply to a single base number.\r\n    Such modifiers should, when applied to an abstract value, be added rather than multiplied together,\r\n    and all multipliers except the first should be reduced by one.\r\n    For example, a &times;2 modifier combined with a &times;3 modifier will result in a total of &times;4 (2 + (3 - 1)) rather than &times;6.\r\n    When applying several multiplicative modifiers to a &quot;real&quot; value (such as a weight or distance),\r\n    normal math should be used and all the multipliers multiplied together.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Stacking:  Characteristics and modifiers of the same type do not generally stack.\r\n    However, please check the section about modifiers  for exceptions to this rule.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The same rule applies to most non-instantaneous spell effects and special abilities.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified (or otherwise dictated by logic), when two similar or identical effects affect\r\n    the same creature or area at the same time, only the most powerful of them applies.\r\n    Note, however, that determining the similarity of two effects is not always trivial and is ultimately up to the DM.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For example, let us say that a creature is first charmed by a wizard\'s spell, then charmed again by a vampire\'s gaze,\r\n    and finally compelled by a cursed magic item.\r\n    In most cases, two charm effects can coexist without conflict, but if the creature in this case\r\n    is forced to make a choice between aiding the wizard or the vampire, the most powerful charm will apply.\r\n    The compulsion, however, is defined by the rules as a more powerful version of a charm effect,\r\n    so in this example it will trump both of the charm effects. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Also note that a single spell can have multiple effects, and unless otherwise specified,\r\n    the same spell can be cast multiple times on the same target. The spell Enhance Senses, for example, can be cast\r\n    several times at a single target, once to give low-light vision, another to give darkvision, etc. \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Timing \r\n     \r\n    Time in a role-playing game is quite fluid, just as it is in movies and literature. When the DM and players agree that few\r\n    interesting things are happening, then days, months, or even years of game time can pass in a second of real time.\r\n    During a complicated situation, on the other hand, a large number of characters may be performing a variety of actions in\r\n    just a few seconds of game time, but this can take hours of real time to play out.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Every action takes a certain amount of game time to perform. For slower actions, the time is measured in &quot;normal&quot; time units:\r\n    minutes (min), hours (h), days, weeks, months, or years. Faster actions, however, are measured in rounds or action points rather than seconds.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Round (r):  A round is a unit of time roughly equal to 6 seconds. In other words, 10 rounds equal one minute.\r\n    During each round, a character can perform either a single full-round action or a combination of faster actions.\r\n    Note, however, that a full-round action can be combined with one or more free actions (those that take 0 AP to perform).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Action Points (AP):  Action Points is a measure of how much a creature can do in a single round.\r\n    When a time is specified in AP, it reflects the number of AP a creature must spend to perform a certain action.\r\n    Typically, a high-level character or monster has more AP to spend per round than one of low level.\r\n    For a low-level character, 1 AP is roughly equivalent to 0.5 seconds, while for a high-level character, it can be as short as 0.15 seconds.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Movement Points (MP):  Movement Points are similar to Action Points but are a measure of a creature\'s rate of movement.\r\n    Movement Points can be used only for movement actions (those with the [Move] descriptor).\r\n    A creature\'s amount of available MP is determined by its speed characteristic, but a limited number of AP can also be used as MP.\r\n    When a time is specified in MP, it reflects the number of MP a creature must spend to perform a certain action.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Encounter (enc):  An encounter is not a fixed amount of time, but it is typically somewhere between half a minute and half an hour.\r\n    It can be an entire combat, from start to finish, a friendly five-minute chat between characters, a few minutes spent climbing a wall, etc.\r\n    In situations where an encounter\'s duration cannot be clearly defined, this time unit is typically limited at one minute per skill level\r\n    (or TL, when skill level is not applicable).\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Characteristics \r\n     \r\n    There are quite a number of characteristics that define a character (or any DM-controlled creature for that matter).\r\n    Some are generated randomly, while others are chosen by the player. Quite a few are simply calculated and derived from other characteristics.\r\n    Some will remain constant throughout the characterโs career, while others will change frequently.\r\n    Some are relatively obscure and abstract, with little or no effect in a typical gaming session, while others provide well-defined modifiers\r\n    to actions the character performs on a regular basis.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Ability Scores \r\n     \r\n    The six ability scores, Strength, Constitution, Dexterity, Intelligence, Wisdom, and Charisma, are among the most basic and important\r\n    characteristics for any character or creature. They affect almost everything a creature does, and a good ability score can give as much\r\n    bonus as several levels of training in a skill.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Ability Scores \r\n     \r\n     Ability \r\n    Abbrev \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	 Effect of No Score (&ndash;, not 0) \r\n   	  \r\n Strength             Str         Affects Fortitude defense, some melee attack rolls, melee weapon damage, some skill action rolls, strength ability checks, and carrying capacity.  Cannot exert force or physically manipulate objects; fail all Str checks; may be allowed to use Dex modifier for some attacks.   Constitution         Con         Affects Fortitude defense, starting hit points, starting stamina points, some skill action rolls, and constitution ability checks.  Immune to ability damage, energy drain, and attacks against Fort defense; have no stamina points and do not suffer fatigue; fail all Con checks.   Dexterity            Dex         Affects Defense Class, Reflex defense, some melee attack rolls, most ranged attack rolls, some skill action rolls, and dexterity ability checks.  Cannot move; fail all Dex checks, and attacks against Ref defense always have full effect; no initiative modifier.   Intelligence         Int         Affects Reflex defense, some magical attack rolls, some skill action rolls, and intelligence ability checks.  Fail all Int checks; can never learn skills; immune to mind-affecting attacks.   Wisdom               Wis         Affects Will defense, starting power points, some magical attack rolls, some skill action rolls, and wisdom ability checks.  Must be an object; have no power points and do not suffer mental fatigue.   Charisma             Cha         Affects Will defense, some magical attack rolls, some skill action rolls, and charisma ability checks.  Must be an object.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Each ability score consists of a base ability score (with a random &quot;bell&quot; distribution between 3 and 18), which is then modified for race and age.\r\n    The main reason that you should keep track of both the base and actual ability scores is that a characterโs race can change in the world of D&amp;D.\r\n    For example, assume that you have a human druid with a low Strength score. If he shapeshifts into a grizzly bear, he will become a lot stronger\r\n    than before (actual ability score increases due to racial modifier), but he will still be relatively weak for a grizzly (base ability score is still the same).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Ability score modifiers are calculated from the actual ability scores, according to the formula or table below.\r\n    Those modifiers are then used for a wide variety of skill checks, ability checks, attack rolls, damage rolls, defenses, etc.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Base ability score:  3-18\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     (Actual) ability score:  Base ability score + racial/template mods + age mod + other modifiers\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Ability modifier:  (Ability score / 2) - 5\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Ability Score Modifiers \r\n     \r\n    Ability Score Ability Modifier \r\n    Ability Score Ability Modifier \r\n    Ability Score Ability Modifier \r\n    Ability Score Ability Modifier \r\n    Ability Score Ability Modifier \r\n   	  \r\n0-1 -5 20-21 +5 40-41 +15 60-61 +25 80-81 +35  2-3 -4 22-23 +6 42-43 +16 62-63 +26 82-83 +36  4-5 -3 24-25 +7 44-45 +17 64-65 +27 84-85 +37  6-7 -2 26-27 +8 46-47 +18 66-67 +28 86-87 +38  8-9 -1 28-29 +9 48-49 +19 68-69 +29 88-89 +39  10-11 0 30-31 +10 50-51 +20 70-71 +30 90-91 +40  12-13 +1 32-33 +11 52-53 +21 72-73 +31 92-93 +41  14-15 +2 34-35 +12 54-55 +22 74-75 +32 94-95 +42  16-17 +3 36-37 +13 56-57 +23 76-77 +33 96-97 +43  18-19 +4 38-39 +14 58-59 +24 78-79 +34 98-99 +44       \r\n \r\n\r\n    Health Scores \r\n     \r\n     Hit Points (HP):  Represent how much physical damage a creature can take before falling unconscious or dying.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     HP = Con + (HP bonus per class and level) + (HP bonus per race and level) &times; size factor + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Stamina Points (SP):  Represent how much physical fatigue a creature can take before becoming exhausted or passing out.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     SP = Con + (SP bonus per class/race and level) + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Power Points (PP):  Represent how much mental fatigue a creature can take before passing out.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     PP = Wis + (PP bonus per class/race and level) + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    An increase or decrease of a creatureโs Con or Wis scores (even a temporary change) immediately leads to a corresponding\r\n    increase or decrease in both maximum and current HP, SP, and/or PP.\r\n    If the creature is already injured or fatigued, an ability decrease can potentially lead to unconsciousness or even death.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Some effects can grant temporary HP, SP, or PP. These are added to the creatureโs current score and are lost before regular points.\r\n    If the effect ends before all the temporary points have been lost, the creatureโs current score drops back to its old, unenhanced value.\r\n    Temporary points can never be healed, naturally or supernaturally.\r\n    Also note that multiple effects that grant temporary health points will not stack; only the highest value counts.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The durability of an object is represented as HP, but very few objects have SP or PP. When an object is reduced to 0 HP, it is destroyed.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Reduced Health Points  (optional rule for more realistic campaigns):\r\n    DMs who want faster and more dangerous combat encounters may consider reducing the health points of all creatures.\r\n    Simply reduce the health points granted by class and racial levels by a given fraction (25% or 50%, for example).\r\n    Another option would be to reduce the health points only of certain creature types, such as humanoids.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Defense Scores \r\n     \r\n     Defense Class (DeC):  A measure of how difficult a creature is to hit with physical attacks.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     DeC (passive) = 10 + size mod + deflection bonus + DeB + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     DeC (active) = DeC (passive) + Dex mod + parry bonus + dodge bonus + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The active DeC is used against attacks that you are aware of and can actively try to avoid.\r\n    The passive DeC is used in other situations, such as when you are flat-footed or surprised, when being attacked\r\n    by an invisible creature, when you have become entangled or paralyzed, etc. Although DeB does apply to passive DeC,\r\n    note that in most surprise situations, a creature will not have been able to allocate any AP to DeB.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The parry bonus can actually be a combination of multiple bonus types.  \r\n    Weapons (natural as well as manufactured ones) and shields usually provide parry bonuses.\r\n    As your skill with a weapon or shield improves, so does the parry bonus you gain from it.\r\n    Magic can also enhance the parrying ability of a weapon or shield.\r\n    Note that only weapons and shields consisting of or carried in primary attack forms count for parry bonuses.\r\n    A human, for example, has two hands that count as primary attacks; secondary attack forms, such as kicks and headbutts,\r\n    do not provide parry bonuses. If you are wielding more than one weapon (or a weapon and a shield, or even two shields),\r\n    you add the parry bonuses for all primary attack forms.\r\n    However, you only gain the highest skill-based bonus, not one skill bonus for each weapon or shield.\r\n    Note that none of the parry-based bonuses apply when calculating passive DeC.\r\n	 \r\n     \r\n    DeB is a special bonus described under the chapter about \r\n    action points .\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Certain attacks may have the ability to bypass or ignore specific modifiers to DeC.\r\n    For example, an incorporeal attacker typically ignores non-magical objects and can therefore ignore a target\'s\r\n    parry bonus for non-magical weapons (including the skill-based parry bonuses for such weapons). \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    DeC can also be calculated for inanimate objects, but they have a Dex of 0 (-5 penalty) and are helpless (-4 penalty).\r\n    In other words, their DeC = 1 + size mod. Note, however, that most objects are resistant or immune to critical hits and coup de grace.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Fortitude defense (Fort):  A measure of how resistant a creature is to attacks against its health and stamina.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Fort = 10 + Str mod + Con mod + TL (total level) + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Reflex defense (Ref):  A measure of how good a creature is at avoiding physical area-effect attacks.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Ref = 10 + Dex mod + Int mod + TL (total level) + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Will defense (Will):  A measure of how resistant a creature is to attacks against its emotions or intellect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Will = 10 + Wis mod + Cha mod + TL (total level) + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    DeC, Fort, Ref, and Will are sometimes grouped together and referred to simply as  Defenses .\r\n    Fort, Ref, and Will are sometimes referred to as  Non-DeC Defenses  or  NDD .\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Resistance Scores \r\n     \r\n     Damage Resistance (DR):  This reflects how resistant a creature (or an object) is to \r\n    physical damage , \r\n    regardless of whether the damage is caused by weapons, claws, teeth, crushing boulders, or a fall from a great height.\r\n    The damage resistance does not apply to energy damage. Every time the creature takes physical damage,\r\n    the damage is reduced by the indicated amount.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    DR can reduce HP as well as SP damage, as long as the source is physical.\r\n    If an attack causes both HP and SP damage, DR will first reduce the SP damage, and then the HP damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Damage Resistance can be granted by thick skin, hard scales, suits of armor, and protective cover.\r\n    DR provided by armor and/or cover is applied separately from and before any DR provided by natural armor or innate resistance.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     DR = Natural DR + armor bonus + cover bonus + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Natural DR is determined by a creature\'s race but can be further affected by templates, magic, etc.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When DR manages to negate all physical damage from an attack, most secondary effects of the attack are also negated.\r\n    This includes effects based on poison, disease, and most special abilities, but it does not apply to touch attacks or energy damage.\r\n    Also note that the defender does not have to roll any skill checks to maintain concentration on difficult tasks when all damage is negated.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Vulnerability to a type of physical damage, type of weapon, or material means that the creature suffers\r\n    additional damage, typically 50% or 100% extra, whenever exposed to that type of damage.\r\n    The extra damage is calculated after any other modifiers due to defenses, magical protection, etc.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Energy Resistance (Acid, Cold, Electricity, Fire, Necrotic, Radiant and/or Sonic Res):  Resistance to a type of \r\n    energy damage , \r\n    reduces the amount of damage taken when exposed to the specified energy type.\r\n    The reduction in damage is made after any other modifiers due to defenses, evasion, magical protection, etc.\r\n    The number indicated for an energy resistance is the maximum sum of HP and SP that can be resisted or absorbed each round.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Energy resistance can reduce HP as well as SP damage, as long as the source is an energy-based attack. If an attack causes both HP and SP damage,\r\n    energy resistance will first reduce the SP damage, and then the HP damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Immunity is equivalent to infinite resistance. The creature never takes any damage from the specified type of energy.\r\n    Immunity also protects against other effects based on the appropriate energy type,\r\n    such as ability damage caused by necrotic energy, blindness caused by radiant energy, and can even prevent\r\n    healing provided by [Radiant]-based healing. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Vulnerability to a type of energy damage means that the creature suffers additional damage,\r\n    typically 50% or 100% extra, whenever exposed to that type of damage.\r\n    The extra damage is calculated after any other modifiers due to defenses, magical protection, etc.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, energy resistance, immunity, and vulnerability does not extend to the creatureโs equipment.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Magic Resistance (MR):  Resistance to magic makes a creature more difficult to affect with many spells and supernatural attacks.\r\n    The creature does not have to be aware of such an attack. The creature can voluntarily and temporarily lower its magic resistance,\r\n    but this requires conscious effort, and it cannot do so selectively for some effects and not for others.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In most cases, MR consists of two components, one level-based and one offset.\r\n    For example, creatures that have natural MR usually specify it as TL + offset,\r\n    skills that grant MR specify it as skill level + offset,\r\n    and spells and magic items that grant MR specify it as PL + offset.\r\n    For creatures that gain MR from multiple sources, calculate total MR as the highest level-based component plus all of the offsets.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    MR works by increasing the difficulty of any spellcasting check (or similar supernatural activation check) that directly affects the protected creature.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Magic resistance applies to most magic spells, psionic powers, and spell-like effects that target the creature in question,\r\n    but it never applies to the creatureโs own spells, powers, items, and abilities.\r\n    Note that magic resistance only applies against actions and spells that have the [MR] descriptor.\r\n    Generally speaking, magic resistance does not normally protect against indirect effects, such as damage caused by an enchanted weapon,\r\n    attacks from a summoned creature, or being entangled by enchanted plants.\r\n    Nor does it protect against magically enhanced senses and illusion magic, since such effects normally apply to the caster or the illusion, respectively.\r\n    Magic resistance can protect against existing and active effects, whenever the resistant creature is first exposed to that effect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Magic resistance protects only the creature with the ability. It does not negate the magic itself nor protect others that are subject to the same magic.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Magic immunity is effectively the same as infinite magic resistance, but it is often limited to certain types or levels of magic.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Ability Damage Resistance:  Reduces the effect of every instance of ability damage by the specified amount.\r\n    Some creatures even enjoy complete immunity to ability damage.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Critical Hit Resistance:  Resistance or immunity to critical hits means that a creature has unusually few sensitive areas\r\n    or that such areas are more effectively protected.\r\n    The resistance adds to the levels of success required to achieve a critical hit, and it applies to any attack that can achieve critical hits.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For example, if a creature has DeC 15 and Critical Hit Resistance 10, an attack result of 15 is enough for a normal hit,\r\n    but a result of 45 (15 + 20 + 10) or better is required for a critical hit.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Objects and creatures that have Critical Hit Resistance of 10 or better take only half damage from piercing attacks (after reduction for DR).\r\n    The reason is that piercing damage is based largely on striking sensitive areas.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Specific Resistance:  Many creatures have resistance or immunity to specific effects, such as charm, fear, sleep, all mind attacks, traps, etc.\r\n    This type of resistance provides a bonus to any defense against such an attack.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Penetrating Hit:  When an attack beats a defense by 10 or more (also known as an exceptional success),\r\n    the damage resistance or energy resistance (if any) is halved.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Social Scores \r\n     \r\n    Social scores are primarily used for creatures that belong to a &quot;civilized&quot; race, but it is also quite possible for\r\n    other creatures to gain widespread influence and repute. For example, a venerable dragon may be known and feared\r\n    across several countries, and a beholder can secretly be in control of a cityโs guild of thieves.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Social Class (SC):  A creatureโs social class is a measure of its status and power in society.\r\n    Note that this refers to the creatureโs own society - an orc king will have a high SC even if neighboring countries may regard him as a criminal.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    SC will change as a result of campaign events, but it does not automatically increase as a character gains experience and levels.\r\n    For example, after performing a quest for the king, a character may be rewarded with land, title, and an increase in SC.\r\n    Or he may commit a crime and suffer a reduction in SC.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Social Classes \r\n     \r\n    SC \r\n     Examples \r\n   	Forms of Address \r\n   	Influence \r\n   	CL Modifier \r\n   	  \r\n-2  Wanted criminal - 0 -1  -1  Outcast, slave - 0 -1  0  Peasant, laborer, hedge knight (sir), sellsword, apprentice Goodman / goodwife 0 0  1  Sworn knight (sir), servant, lesser merchant, acolyte Sir / Lady (Sir) +5 0  2  Retainer, landed knight (sir), merchant, master Sir / Lady (Sir) +10 0  3  Minor noble (lord), greater knight (sir), greater merchant Lord / Lady (Lord) +15 +1  4  Major noble Milord / Milady +20 +2  5  Royal family Highness +25 +3  6  King, queen, emperor, empress Majesty +30 +4       \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Influence: The bonus influence points should be used to gain influence over an appropriate organization, family, clan, or even nation.\r\n    CL Modifier: A creature\'s social class affects its challenge level (CL), due to its power in society and the potential trouble it can cause for its enemies.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The examples in the table above are only the most generic ones in a standard feudal system.\r\n    Most societies will have a large number of special positions and titles (sheriffs, magistrates, advisors, cardinals, prophets, etc.)\r\n    that can grant status as high as major nobles.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Wealth Class (WC):  This is a measure of a creatureโs (or an organizationโs) resources, assets, holdings, and sources of income\r\n    rather than a measure of its treasure and hard cash.\r\n    WC above 0 will actually generate an automatic income and can be treated as a renewable resource.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A creatureโs WC also determines the amount of money that other individuals and organizations are prepared to lend to him.\r\n    The exact limit may vary, but the maximum total loan should be roughly the same as the minimum investment required to reach the class (see the table below).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    By default, a creature born to a certain SC will have a WC at the same level.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Wealth Classes \r\n     \r\n    WC \r\n     Description \r\n   	Renewable Income \r\n   	Minimum Investment \r\n   	  \r\n-2  Seriously in debt. 0 0  -1  Destitute; no resources or possessions. 0 1 gp  0  Poor; lives in a shack and eats very simple meals; a few cheap possessions. 0 2 gp  1  Stable; owns a small homestead (or lives with a master); may own a few luxuries or heirlooms; may have a couple of apprentices. 0.1-1 sp/day 10 gp  2  Well off; claim to some land or owns profitable business; some large expenditures are possible; some stockpiled resources; may have numerous assistants and warehouses; a knight may have a small holdfast and a garrison. 1-10 sp/day 500 gp  3  Wealthy; extensive holdings; stockpiled resources; could have a small fleet of ships or a major castle; may employ dozens or hundreds of men. 10-100 sp/day 5000 gp  4  Very wealthy; multiple large properties or key territory; hundreds or thousands of vassals. 10-100 gp/day 50,000 gp  5  Tremendously wealthy; enormous territory, with many holdings and assets; thousands or tens of thousands of vassals. 100-1000 gp/day 500,000 gp  6  Fabulously wealthy; enormous territory and plum resources; can lend large sums to other lords and organizations. 1000-10,000 gp/day 5,000,000 gp       \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Renewable income: This is the amount of money typically generated per day from owned resources, businesses, and holdings.\r\n    Minimum investment: This is the minimum amount of money that must be invested to progress from the previous class to this one.\r\n    80% of this money can be regained by selling resources and holdings, dropping back to the previous class in the process.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    A large purchase (on the order of 100 times the daily income) can temporarily decrease a creatureโs WC.\r\n    Likewise, a large windfall (of a similar magnitude) can temporarily increase a creatureโs WC.\r\n    Such decreases and increases will last 2d4 months.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Major events (earthquakes, city fires, drought, good or bad weather, wars, new mines or resources, etc.)\r\n    can cause the WC of both individuals and organizations to fluctuate by as much as ยฑ2.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Influence (Infl):  This is a measure of a creatureโs affiliation with and power over another individual,\r\n    an organization, a family or clan, or even a region.\r\n    It is not unusual for an individual to have multiple separate influences, each over a separate entity.\r\n    For example, a high-ranking member of a guild will have influence in that guild, but he may also wield some influence in the city\r\n    where he lives and over a couple of government officials he knows well.\r\n    Note that influence is not always based on friendship and loyalty; it can also be based on fear, blackmail, bribes, etc.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    It should be noted that influence is not strictly one-way. Increased power and influence over an organization will often lead to\r\n    more responsibilities, duties, and obligations as well as privileges.\r\n    Although you can use influence in an organization to command those of a lower rank or request favors from those of equal rank,\r\n    you have a duty or obligation to obey commands from those of higher rank.\r\n    Also, a friendly relationship between two or more individuals will usually result in mutual influences between those individuals.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, a creature has a total number of influence points based on Cha and level.\r\n    However, this can be further affected by the creatureโs SC, various campaign events, character actions,\r\n    or even the demise of an individual or organization with which one has influence.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Total Infl = Cha + (Infl bonus per class/race and level) + SC bonus + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most creatures (especially player characters) should be able to decide themselves how to distribute their\r\n    influence points (and also what that influence is based on).\r\n    Nevertheless, there are some limitations, and every decision has to be approved by the DM.\r\n    Influence points gained from level should be spent mostly on an organization or individual associated with the creatureโs class.\r\n    For example, a cleric will gain influence in his church, a rogue in his thievesโ guild or network of contacts, etc.\r\n    Influence points gained from SC should be spent on the focus of and reason for that social status.\r\n    For example, most nobles have been born into their role, title, and status, so their SC-based influence should be spent within\r\n    their family and household.\r\n    Note that a society will often have cultural traditions that may affect influence; for example, a noble who joins the clergy\r\n    may in some societies lose his name, title, and some or all of the power granted by his family name.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Except under extreme circumstances, a maximum of 20 influence points can be spent on a single individual.\r\n    For organizations and families, influence is normally limited to 10 points for non-members, but it is unlimited for members.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Reputation (Rep):  This determines how famous or infamous a creature is and also the reason for its fame.\r\n    A creatureโs total reputation is typically divided into a couple of separate qualities that the creature is best known for.\r\n    Some qualities may be rather generic descriptions, such as bold, brave, carouser, clever, dangerous, dedicated, fierce,\r\n    generous, honest, honorable, loyal, rake, strong, stubborn, valiant, well-educated, wise, etc.\r\n    Qualities can also be quite specific, such as seaโs master, berserker, horse lord, magi, defender of the crown,\r\n    sheriff of Nulb, or slayer of Rork the Robber-Baron.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Total Rep = TL (total level) + SC + WC + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A creature with a total reputation of 1 to 5 is typically known within its village or neighborhood,\r\n    6 to 10 within a city or county, 11 to 15 within a nation, 16 to 20 within the neighboring countries,\r\n    and 21 or more within the known world. Use this only as a rough guideline, however.\r\n    A powerful dragon that has been buried and dormant in a desert for thousands of years\r\n    is not likely to be very famous (except maybe to bards and historians).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Reputation points granted by SC and WC should be assigned to appropriate qualities, such as powerful, rich, royal advisor,\r\n    smuggler lord, merchant king, etc. Characters should choose how to distribute their own level-based reputation points,\r\n    but this distribution is always subject to DM approval.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Reputation and reputation qualities can and will change over time. As a reputation grows and time passes,\r\n    the quality will often become more generalized. For example, a warrior who first gains fame as a โtroll slayerโ\r\n    may change the reputation quality to a more generic โbold warriorโ as his fame continues to grow.\r\n    Many campaign events can grant positive or negative reputations, regardless of an individualโs level or intentions.\r\n    Repeatedly acting against oneโs reputation, such as a โbold warriorโ acting cowardly, will inevitably lower it.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Note that reputation represents what people think and not necessarily what is true.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Personality Characteristics \r\n     \r\n    Alignment:  This is a rough representation of a creatureโs personality and its moral and ethical outlook on life.\r\n    It is based on two separate scales, one going from good to evil, and another going from lawful to chaotic.\r\n    Each of the two scales actually covers a wide range of behaviors, but alignment is often simplified by dividing it into just nine separate categories.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Players should be free to role-play their characters any way they want, so alignment should primarily be used for monsters and NPCs.\r\n    It is a useful guideline for a DM when role-playing a wide variety of strange creatures.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Alignment Descriptions \r\n     \r\n     Alignment \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Lawful Good  A lawful good character acts as a good person is expected or required to act. She combines a commitment to oppose evil with the discipline to fight relentlessly. She tells the truth, keeps her word, helps those in need, and speaks out against injustice. A lawful good character hates to see the guilty go unpunished.   Neutral Good  A neutral good character does the best that a good person can do. He is devoted to helping others. He works with kings and magistrates but does not feel beholden to them.   Chaotic Good  A chaotic good character acts as his conscience directs him with little regard for what others expect of him. He makes his own way, but he\'s kind and benevolent. He believes in goodness and right but has little use for laws and regulations. He hates it when people try to intimidate others and tell them what to do. He follows his own moral compass, which, although good, may not agree with that of society.   Lawful Neutral  A lawful neutral character acts as law, tradition, or a personal code directs her. Order and organization are paramount to her. She may believe in personal order and live by a code or standard, or she may believe in order for all and favor a strong, organized government.   Neutral  A neutral character does what seems to be a good idea. She doesn\'t feel strongly one way or the other when it comes to good vs. evil or law vs. chaos. Most neutral characters exhibit a lack of conviction or bias rather than a commitment to neutrality. Such a character thinks of good as better than evil - after all, she would rather have good neighbors and rulers than evil ones. Still, she\'s not personally committed to upholding good in any abstract or universal way. Some neutral characters, on the other hand, commit themselves philosophically to neutrality. They see good, evil, law, and chaos as prejudices and dangerous extremes. They advocate the middle way of neutrality as the best, most balanced road in the long run.   Chaotic Neutral  A chaotic neutral character follows his whims. He is an individualist first and last. He values his own liberty but doesn\'t strive to protect others\' freedom. He avoids authority, resents restrictions, and challenges traditions. A chaotic neutral character does not intentionally disrupt organizations as part of a campaign of anarchy. To do so, he would have to be motivated either by good (and a desire to liberate others) or evil (and a desire to make those different from himself suffer). A chaotic neutral character may be unpredictable, but his behavior is not totally random. He is not as likely to jump off a bridge as to cross it.   Lawful Evil  A lawful evil villain methodically takes what he wants within the limits of his code of conduct without regard for whom it hurts. He cares about tradition, loyalty, and order but not about freedom, dignity, or life. He plays by the rules but without mercy or compassion. He is comfortable in a hierarchy and would like to rule, but is willing to serve. He condemns others not according to their actions but according to race, religion, homeland, or social rank. He is loath to break laws or promises. This reluctance comes partly from his nature and partly because he depends on order to protect himself from those who oppose him on moral grounds. Some lawful evil villains have particular taboos, such as not killing in cold blood (but having underlings do it) or not letting children come to harm (if it can be helped). They imagine that these compunctions put them above unprincipled villains. Some lawful evil people and creatures commit themselves to evil with a zeal like that of a crusader committed to good. Beyond being willing to hurt others for their own ends, they take pleasure in spreading evil as an end unto itself. They may also see doing evil as part of a duty to an evil deity or master.   Neutral Evil  A neutral evil villain does whatever she can get away with. She is out for herself, pure and simple. She sheds no tears for those she kills, whether for profit, sport, or convenience. She has no love of order and holds no illusion that following laws, traditions, or codes would make her any better or more noble. On the other hand, she doesn\'t have the restless nature or love of conflict that a chaotic evil villain has. Some neutral evil villains hold up evil as an ideal, committing evil for its own sake. Most often, such villains are devoted to evil deities or secret societies.   Chaotic Evil  A chaotic evil character does whatever his greed, hatred, and lust for destruction drive him to do. He is hot-tempered, vicious, arbitrarily violent, and unpredictable. If he is simply out for whatever he can get, he is ruthless and brutal. If he is committed to the spread of evil and chaos, he is even worse. Thankfully, his plans are haphazard, and any groups he joins or forms are poorly organized. Typically, chaotic evil people can be made to work together only by force, and their leader lasts only as long as he can thwart attempts to topple or assassinate him.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    In some cases, the rules will refer to alignments opposed to or compatible with a base alignment.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Opposed alignment:  Any alignment opposite to the base alignment along one or both scales.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Diametrically opposed alignment:  An alignment opposite to the base alignment along both scales.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Compatible alignment:  An alignment within one step of the base alignment along one (but not both) scales.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Relative Alignments \r\n     \r\n     Alignment \r\n   	 Opposed \r\n   	 Diametrically Opposed \r\n   	 Compatible \r\n   	  \r\n Lawful Good  Any chaotic, any evil  Chaotic evil  Lawful good, neutral good, lawful neutral   Neutral Good  Any evil  Neutral evil  Any good, neutral   Chaotic Good  Any lawful, any evil  Lawful evil  Neutral good, chaotic good, chaotic neutral   Lawful Neutral  Any chaotic  Chaotic neutral  Any lawful, neutral   Neutral  None  None  Neutral good, lawful neutral, chaotic neutral, neutral evil   Chaotic Neutral  Any lawful  Lawful neutral  Any chaotic, neutral   Lawful Evil  Any chaotic, any good  Chaotic good  Lawful neutral, lawful evil, neutral evil   Neutral Evil  Any good  Neutral good  Any evil, neutral   Chaotic Evil  Any lawful, any good  Lawful good  Chaotic neutral, neutral evil, chaotic evil       \r\n \r\n\r\n    Level Characteristics \r\n     \r\n    One of the most crucial characteristics of any creature is its level. Level is quite simply a rough indication of how powerful a creature is.\r\n    For many intelligent creatures, time and experience will lead to a gradual increase in level.\r\n    This, in turn, will lead to more health points, improved skills, and many other benefits.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Experience Points (XP):  This is a measure of how much total experience a character has accumulated in his lifetime.\r\n    When a character defeats opponents and other challenges, the DM will reward him with an appropriate number of XP.\r\n    The number of XP determines when a creature gains a level, as shown on the table below.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Class Level (ClL):  This is the number of levels a creature has in a certain class.\r\n    A creature can also have different levels in a number of separate classes.\r\n    Class levels are most commonly shown as the abbreviation for the class followed by the level.\r\n    For example, 5 levels in the fighter class is abbreviated as Ftr5, while 6 rogue levels combined with 3 wizard levels are abbreviated as Rog6/Wiz3.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Racial Level (RL):  Many creatures are so physically powerful that just belonging to their race counts as a certain number of &quot;bonus&quot; levels.\r\n    For example, an ogre that is also a level 5 fighter is a more powerful and dangerous opponent than a human level 5 fighter,\r\n    and this is represented by a number of racial ogre levels.\r\n    Racial levels are technically treated as levels in one of the classes associated with the creature\'s culture.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Total Level (TL):  A creatureโs total level is simply the sum of all its class and racial levels.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     TL = &sum;ClL + RL \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Challenge Level (CL):  This is a measure of how challenging a creature is as an opponent.\r\n    In many cases, CL is equal to TL, but sometimes a creature has special abilities, social class, etc.\r\n    that can make it more (or less) dangerous than its TL would indicate.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     CL = TL + CL modifier \r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Levels and Experience \r\n     \r\n    TL (or CL) \r\n    XP \r\n    AP \r\n   	  \r\n1 0 11  2 1000 12  3 3000 13  4 6000 14  5 10000 15  6 15000 16  7 21000 17  8 28000 18  9 36000 19  10 45000 20  11 55000 21  12 66000 22  13 78000 23  14 91000 24  15 105000 25  16 120000 26  17 136000 27  18 153000 28  19 171000 29  20 190000 30  21 210000 31  22 231000 32  23 253000 33  24 276000 34  25 300000 35  26 325000 36  27 351000 37  28 378000 38  29 406000 39  30 435000 40       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    CL (when it differs from TL) should be used to determine the XP cost per level.\r\n    TL is still used to determine the number of action points.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Action Points (AP):  Action Points is a measure of how much a creature can do in a single round.\r\n    The available amount of AP is determined by TL, so for a character this amount will typically increase as the character\r\n    gains experience and becomes more skilled.\r\n    During combat, action points can be used for actions and/or allocated to three different combat bonuses: \r\n    Attack Bonus (AB), Damage Bonus (DaB), and Defense Bonus (DeB) .\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Skill Points:  As a creature gains levels, it also gains skill points (determined by the class).\r\n    These points can be used to learn new skills or improve already known skills.\r\n    Skill points have to be spent when the level is gained, and they canโt be saved for future use.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Improvement Points (IP):  Characters and other exceptional creatures gain 5 improvement points per level.\r\n    Improvements points can be saved and accumulated for future use.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    Improvement points can be used to buy the following benefits:\r\n     \r\n    \r\n	\r\n   	Improvements \r\n     \r\n     Improvement \r\n    IP Cost \r\n    Max Bonus \r\n      \r\n Improvement bonus to Str, Con, Dex, Int, Wis, or Cha 10 per +1 +5   Improvement bonus to DeC 10 per +1 +5   Improvement bonus to Fort, Ref, or Will 5 per +1 +5   Improvement bonus to HP, SP, or PP 2 per +1 +25   Improvement bonus to skill level 10 per +1 +5   Gain permanent secondary access to skill. Skill prerequisites still apply. 10 per skill -   Improve permanent secondary skill access to primary access. 20 per skill -       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Advantages and Disadvantages  (optional rule for more varied characters): Characters can spend improvement points to buy special advantages,\r\n    and they can acquire additional improvement points by accepting special disadvantages.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    All advantages and disadvantages are subject to DM approval. Many of them should typically only be allowed for newly\r\n    generated characters, and no character should be allowed to buy advantages for more than 10 IP nor acquire more than\r\n    10 IP from disadvantages. However, the DM should feel free to award or require IP for advantages or disadvantages\r\n    gained later in a character\'s career. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In most cases, a character should be able to pay IP to reduce or remove a disadvantage acquired at an earlier level.\r\n    The player and DM should together try to explain exactly how this is accomplished.\r\n    Note that a character should not be allowed to get rid of a disadvantage without paying the required IP.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Advantages \r\n     \r\n    # \r\n     Advantage \r\n    IP Cost \r\n      \r\n1  Adapt to environmental effect (reduce penalties) Usually 5 per point  2  Allied organization/individual 2  3  Disease immunity 2 per disease  4  Good reputation (improvement bonus for some social actions) 2 for +4 bonus, 5 for +8, 10 for +12  5  Longevity (add 50% to age ranges) 5  6  Magically gifted (+2 improvement bonus on all spell-related skill checks (not attacks), but same bonus applies to such checks against you) 5  7  Magically resistant (+2 improvement bonus to MR but also -2 improvement penalty on all spell-related skill checks) 5  8  Member of organization (bonus influence points) 1 per 2 infl  9  Permanent beneficial spell 1 per 2 PL  10  Poison immunity 2 per poison  11  Reduce cultural or racial penalty Usually 10 per point  12  Sleep immunity 5  13  Special equipment (family heirloom) 1 per 500 sp  14  Unusual training (choose any class for background skills and racial levels) 15       \r\n	\r\n	\r\n   	Disadvantages \r\n     \r\n    # \r\n     Disadvantage \r\n    IP Cost \r\n      \r\n1  Addiction -2  2  Allergy -2  3  Bad reputation (improvement penalty on some social actions) -2 for -4 penalty, -5 for -8, -10 for -12  4  Bastardy (-2 improvement penalty on some social actions) -2  5  Color blindness -2  6  Crippled (one or more limbs) -5 for -2 penalty with one limb, -10 for missing or useless limb  7  Dark secret (exposure would result in reduced SC or WC) Varies  8  Disease (chronic) Varies  9  Distinguishing mark (hard to conceal and easily identified) -2  10  Duty to organization/individual -2  11  Enemy organization/individual -2  12  Eyesight, impaired -5 for -10 Spot penalty, -10 for blindness  13  Fury (you are easily provoked and fight with abandon; Will check required to inflict non-lethal damage or break off a fight) -2 for +5 vs Will, -5 for +10  14  Hearing, impaired -5 for -10 Listen penalty, -10 for deafness  15  Insanity or amnesia Varies  16  Low SC -2 for SC -1, -5 for SC -2  17  Low WC -2 for WC -1, -5 for WC -2  18  Mute (unable to communicate verbally or perform actions with a verbal component) -5  19  Obesity -2 per +1 EC  20  Permanent curse (debilitating spell) -1 per 2 PL  21  Phobia -2 for mild, -5 for severe  22  Scars, disfiguring (-2 improvement penalty on some social actions; easily identified) -2       \r\n    \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Random Advantages and Disadvantages  (optional rule for more varied characters):\r\n    The player or DM can roll randomly for advantages and disadvantages. Roll d% &rarr;\r\n    01-50: No ad or disad, 51-75: One random advantage and roll again, 76-100: One random disadvantage and roll again.\r\n    The character\'s improvement points should be adjusted accordingly.\r\n     \r\n    \r\n     \r\n     Power Level (PL):  Power Level is used for all supernatural creatures and objects,\r\n    and it is a measure of how supernatural they are.\r\n    A high PL makes the creature or object easier to detect with magic and supernatural senses but\r\n    also more resistant to dispelling, anti-magic, and wild magic.\r\n    Most supernatural creatures have a PL equal to their TL.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Racial Characteristics \r\n     \r\n     Race/Creature:  This is the species an individual belongs to. Some races will also have a variety of subraces.\r\n    For example, sylvan and drow elves are two subraces of the elven race, with very different racial traits and temperaments.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Creature type and subtype:  Each creature belongs to a specific creature type and subtype.\r\n    This will sometimes affect or determine the efficiency of special powers, spells, and magic items.\r\n    For example, some magic weapons deal greater damage to certain creature types,\r\n    and some skills teach you how to better track and fight specific creature types.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Template:  This is a special racial modification that can be added on top of a base race.\r\n    Vampiricism and lycanthropy are two well-known examples of templates.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Culture:  This represents the upbringing and background of a creature.\r\n    Most importantly, it determines which class or classes to use when choosing background skills.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Size category (Sz):  Every creature or object will receive certain modifiers based on its size, as shown on the table below.\r\n    For many objects, the objectโs own size category is specified (\"object size\") as well as the size category of the creature meant to use it (\"made-for-size\").\r\n    For example, a dagger made for a Medium-sized wielder is still just a Tiny object.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Size Categories \r\n     \r\n    Size \r\n     Description \r\n    Att/DeC Mod \r\n   	Grapple Mod \r\n   	Att Spd Mod \r\n   	RL HP Mult. \r\n   	Weight Limit Mult. \r\n   	Max. Length (m) \r\n   	Max. Volume (cb.m) \r\n   	Space \r\n   	Reach (sq) \r\n   	Maneuver. Mod \r\n   	  \r\n-4  Fine (F) +8 -16 -4 ร0.25 ร0.1 0.15 0.0001 - 0 +2  -3  Diminutive (D) +4 -12 -3 ร0.5 ร0.25 0.3 0.0005 1/4x1/4 sq 0 +1  -2  Tiny (T) +2 -8 -2 ร1 ร0.5 0.6 0.004 1/2x1/2 sq 1 +1  -1  Small (S) +1 -4 -1 ร1 ร0.75 1.2 0.03 1x1 sq 1 0  0  Medium (M) 0 0 0 ร1 ร1 2.5 0.25 1x1 sq 1 0  +1  Large (L) -1 +4 +1 ร1.5 ร2 5 2 2x2 sq 1 0  +2  Huge (H) -2 +8 +2 ร2 ร4 10 15 3x3 sq 2 -1  +3  Gargantuan (G) -4 +12 +3 ร3 ร8 20 120 4x4 sq 3 -1  +4  Colossal (C) -8 +16 +4 ร4 ร16   6x6 sq or more 4 -2       \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Att/DeC Mod: This size-based modifier is added to all attack rolls that a creature makes against DeC, \r\n    and the same modifier is added to the creature\'s own DeC.\r\n    The reason for this modifier is that small creatures are harder to hit than large ones, \r\n    and since Medium size is used as a common reference, a similar modifier also has to be applied to attack rolls.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Grapple Mod: This size-based modifier is used for grapple attacks (but not for initiating a grapple).\r\n    Att Spd Mod: A size-based modifier for the AP cost of weapon attacks.\r\n    RL HP Mult: Hit points (HP) gained from racial levels (RL) should be multiplied by this factor.\r\n    Weight Limit Multiplier: Multiply the creature\'s strength-based weight limits by this factor.\r\n    Space: The number of squares a creature of this size occupies.\r\n    This includes room for typical combat maneuvers, so objects of this size usually occupy fewer squares, and most creatures can squeeze into smaller areas/volumes.\r\n    Reach: This is the base reach of a creature of this size.\r\n    Note that actual reach can be further modified by body type and weapons.\r\n    Also note that reach counts fully in all directions, including diagonally.\r\n    Maneuverability Mod: This is a modifier to maneuverability for all types of movement.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Body category (Body):  This is a description of a creature\'s shape and body configuration.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Body Categories \r\n     \r\n     Body Type \r\n   	Weight Limit Mult. \r\n   	Height Mult. \r\n   	Reach Mod \r\n   	Ground Maneuver. \r\n   	 Default Traits \r\n   	  \r\n Generic ร1 ร1 0 0     Biped ร1 ร2 +1 0  Can wear humanoid armor Can wear humanoid clothing Can wear cloak Can wear belt Can wear necklace or amulet    Biped, winged ร1 ร2 +1 0  Can wear winged humanoid armor Can wear winged humanoid clothing Can wear belt Can wear necklace or amulet    Quadruped ร1.5 ร1 0 +1  Can wear quadruped armor Can wear necklace or amulet Can wear saddle and carry rider(s)    Quadruped, winged ร1.5 ร1 0 +1  Can wear winged quadruped armor Can wear necklace or amulet Can wear saddle and carry rider(s)    Multiped ร1.5 ร1 0 +1  Can wear multiped armor Can wear necklace or amulet Can wear saddle and carry rider(s)    Multiped, winged ร1.5 ร1 0 +1