reature has been alive.\r\n    In a few rare cases, a creature may suffer unnatural aging or may even be able to halt or reverse natural aging.\r\n    If that is the case, it becomes necessary to track physical and mental age separately.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Age category:  A creatureโs age and race determine which age category it belongs to.\r\n    Age category, in turn, will affect ability scores and racial level for most creature types, as shown in the table below.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Age Category Effects (animals and humanoids) \r\n     \r\n     Age Category \r\n    Str \r\n    Con \r\n    Dex \r\n    Int \r\n    Wis \r\n    Cha \r\n    RL Multiplier \r\n    Size Mod \r\n      \r\n Child -4 -2 +2 0 -4 0 ร0.5 -1   Juvenile -2 0 0 0 -2 0 ร0.75 0   Adult 0 0 0 0 0 0 ร1 0   Mature -1 -1 -1 +1 +1 +1 ร1 0   Old -3 -3 -3 +2 +2 +2 ร1 0   Venerable -6 -6 -6 +3 +3 +3 ร1 0       \r\n\r\n    \r\n   	Age Category Effects (aberrations, dragons, plants, and undead) \r\n     \r\n     Age Category \r\n    Str \r\n    Con \r\n    Dex \r\n    Int \r\n    Wis \r\n    Cha \r\n    RL Multiplier \r\n    Size Mod \r\n      \r\n Child -4 -2 +2 0 -4 0 ร0.5 -1   Juvenile -2 0 0 0 -2 0 ร0.75 0   Adult 0 0 0 0 0 0 ร1 0   Mature +1 +1 0 +1 +1 +1 ร1.5 0   Old +2 +2 0 +2 +2 +2 ร2 +1   Venerable +3 +3 0 +3 +3 +3 ร3 +1       \r\n\r\n     \r\n    RL Multiplier: A creature\'s RL should be multiplied by this age-based factor.\r\n    Size Modifier: A creature\'s size can also vary with age, according to this modifier.\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Constructs, elementals, and outsiders do not normally have age categories or age-based adjustments.\r\n    Some, however, may use the ability adjustments for animals and humanoids.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Fate Points (FP):  These are points that can be used in a situation where all else has failed.\r\n    They are possessed by individuals that have important destinies, more specifically the player characters\r\n    and their key opponents. Fate points can be used as follows:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         One point can change any failed check to a basic success. \r\n         One point can change an opponentโs successful check into a failure. \r\n         One point can change a recent death (caused by HP loss) into unconsciousness (-1 HP). \r\n         One point lets a character recover immediately from any single condition (e.g. compelled or stunned). \r\n         Two points can be used to provide a miraculous escape from an otherwise certain death.\r\n        The DM dictates the specifics but should not give out any bonuses other than mere survival.\r\n        The character can still lose treasured items or suffer some severe and long-lasting injury. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Fate points are not automatically regenerated. Once used, they are gone forever.\r\n    Nevertheless, the DM should sometimes reward characters with new fate points,\r\n    but only when they have accomplished something extraordinary.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Characteristics Dependency Chart \r\n     \r\n    The following figure shows the characteristics that are common to most creatures. It also shows their dependencies and relationships,\r\n    with the most basic and constant characteristics at the top. Whenever one of your characteristics gets updated,\r\n    you can use the graph to determine which other characteristics will be indirectly affected by the change.\r\n     \r\n	\r\n    \r\n     \r\n    Note that spells and magic items can affect almost any characteristic, and this is not shown in the chart above.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Actions and Action Checks \r\n     \r\n    Actions  \r\n    cover everything that a character can do. Some actions are very simple to perform,\r\n    such as walking across a room or shouting a warning to a friend.\r\n    Unless there are extreme circumstances (walking across a slippery floor during an earthquake, for example),\r\n    such actions are automatically successful. Other actions, such as hitting a target with a thrown dagger,\r\n    climbing a cliff wall, or deciphering a tome written in an ancient language, can be more or less difficult,\r\n    and they always carry a chance of failure. Those actions will typically require a die roll to determine the level of success or failure.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Access to Actions \r\n     \r\n    Many actions can be attempted by practically any character or creature, regardless of class or skill.\r\n    In other words, such actions can be used even if the character has 0 skill levels in the action\'s associated skill (if any).\r\n    These actions are designated with the [Untrained] descriptor.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Actions that do not allow untrained use can only be used if the character has explicitly gained access to the action,\r\n    usually by belonging to a certain race or by having enough levels in the action\'s associated skill.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Special access and usage rules apply for skills with specializations. For an action that can be used untrained,\r\n    the character counts half his actual skill levels when using an untrained specialization.\r\n    For an action that cannot be used untrained, the character can only attempt actions with specializations that he knows.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Performing Action Checks \r\n     \r\n    The core mechanism for resolving any action is known as a d20 check and is quite simple:\r\n    roll d20, add the appropriate modifiers, and compare the result against a target number\r\n    (typically a difficulty class, defense score, or an opposing action check).\r\n    If the total is equal to or higher than the target number, the action succeeds. If it is lower, the action fails.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Whenever an action is to be performed, follow these steps:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Select the action you want to perform (make sure you have the necessary skills and skill levels). \r\n         Select any variable options and parameters (such as range, target, etc). \r\n         Start the action. \r\n         At the end of the activation time, roll the d20 action check (if any) and apply modifiers.\r\n            If the action has multiple mandatory skills, use the highest skill level for the check.\r\n            If you are distracted or hurt during the activation time, additional action checks will often be required\r\n            to maintain concentration and complete the action. \r\n         Deduct costs (in SP, PP, money, etc). \r\n         Determine and apply the results and effects. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Certain types of d20 checks are so common that they have their own names, as shown here:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         d20 check \r\n         Roll d20, add modifiers, and compare the result against the target number. \r\n         Skill check \r\n         d20 check using a skill against a difficulty class (DC) or opposing skill. \r\n         Ability check \r\n         d20 check using an ability mod against a DC. \r\n         Attack roll \r\n         d20 check using attack modifiers against a defense. \r\n         Supernatural activation check (also known as a spellcasting check) \r\n         A skill check specifically used to cast a spell (or activate a supernatural ability). \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A few example actions and their d20 checks:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Climb a wall \r\n         d20 + Athletics skill + Str mod + other mods against the wallโs DC. \r\n         Sneaking \r\n         d20 + Stealth skill + Dex mod + other mods against opposing 10 + Perception skill + Wis mod + other mods. \r\n         Break door \r\n         d20 + Brawling skill + Str mod against doorโs DC. \r\n         Weapon attack \r\n         d20 + ability mod + attack mod + other mods against DeC. \r\n         Magic attack \r\n         d20 + ability mod + attack mod + other mods against appropriate defense. \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Actions with Multiple Action Checks \r\n     \r\n    Although most actions require zero or one action checks, there are some that require multiple separate action checks.\r\n    See below for three different examples, all of them attacks of one type or another:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Example 1: A disintegrating ray typically requires two attack rolls, one against DeC to hit the target,\r\n    and a second one against Fort to then overcome the target\'s fortitude and deal maximum damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Example 2: A large fireball that targets multiple opponents will require a separate attack roll against each target.\r\n    Unless otherwise described in the effect, damage is rolled once and applied equally against all targets,\r\n    but the separate attack rolls can result in varying degrees of success and failure against the different targets,\r\n    in turn resulting in different amounts of damage being inflicted.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Example 3: A combatant is using Multi-Attack to attack with both a sword and a dagger simultaneously,\r\n    possibly even against two different targets.\r\n    In this case, the Multi-Attack action counts as two separate attacks, and each of these attacks is resolved separately\r\n    (albeit simultaneously), with separate attack rolls as well as damage rolls.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The fact that a single action can consist of multiple attacks and/or multiple action checks means that it will\r\n    sometimes be important to note whether a modifier applies to an action, an action check, an attack, or an attack roll.\r\n    For example, if you happen to have a bonus that applies to your next attack roll, and you cast a fireball spell,\r\n    the bonus will only apply to the first of the spell\'s attack rolls (typically against the target closest to the center).\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Open-Ended d20 Checks \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, all d20 checks use an open-ended d20 roll.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    On an initial roll of a natural 20, roll again and add the new result to the first.\r\n    A second roll of 20 allows another reroll, and so forth. Some special checks produce exceptional results more often than normal\r\n    and allow open-ended rerolls on rolls lower than 20, such as on 19 to 20 or 18 to 20.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    On an initial roll of a natural 1, roll again and subtract 20 from the result.\r\n    If this roll results in another 1, roll again and subtract 40 instead, and so forth.\r\n    Some special checks have a greater than normal risk of failure and require open-ended rerolls even on rolls higher than 1, such as on 1 to 2 or 1 to 3.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Difficulty Classes (DC) \r\n     \r\n    A difficulty class is an estimate of how difficult an action is to perform successfully.\r\n    It is the number your action check has to match or exceed in order to be a success.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		 \r\n	The following table shows some examples of DCs:\r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	\r\n   	Difficulty Classes \r\n     \r\n     Difficulty \r\n    DC \r\n     Example \r\n      \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Very easy \r\n	0 \r\n	 Notice something large in plain sight \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Easy \r\n	5 \r\n	 Climb a knotted rope \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Average \r\n	10 \r\n	 Hear an approaching man in armor \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Tough \r\n	15 \r\n	 Rig a wagon wheel to fall off \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Challenging \r\n	20 \r\n	 Swim in stormy water \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Formidable \r\n	25 \r\n	 Open an average lock \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Heroic \r\n	30 \r\n	 Leap across a 10 m chasm \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Very heroic \r\n	40 \r\n	 Hear an owl flying by (when sleeping) \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Regardless of skill levels and difficulty classes, the DM can choose to disallow or severely penalize certain illogical actions.\r\n    For example, even if a crocodile has a high strength score and a few skill levels in Athletics, it should not be able to climb a tree.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Physical and Mental Action Modifiers \r\n     \r\n    Some circumstance modifiers are common enough that they have their own abbreviations.\r\n    These abbreviations are used in the action checks where appropriate, \r\n    PAM for Physical Action Modifier and MAM for Mental Action Modifier.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Generic Action Modifiers \r\n     \r\n     Condition \r\n    PAM \r\n    MAM \r\n      \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Physical condition (SP) 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Fatigued \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Exhausted \r\n	-6 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Mental condition (PP) 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Tired \r\n	 \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Drained \r\n	 \r\n	-6 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Taking damage during action \r\n	- damage dealt (HP+SP+PP) \r\n	- damage dealt (HP+SP+PP) \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Taking continuous damage \r\n	- ยฝ of damage taken per round (HP+SP+PP) \r\n	- ยฝ of damage taken per round (HP+SP+PP) \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Exposed to non-damaging effect during action \r\n	- PL of effect \r\n	- PL of effect \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Conditions 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Dazzled \r\n	-1 \r\n	-1 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Shaken or frightened \r\n	-2 \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Squeezing through tight space \r\n	-4 \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Within a swarm \r\n	-4 \r\n	-4 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Entangled 2  \r\n	-4 \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Grappling or pinned \r\n	-4 \r\n	-8 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Obstructions on ground 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Light obstructions \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Severe obstructions \r\n	-4 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Slippery ground 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Slightly slippery \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Very slippery \r\n	-4 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 On mount or vehicle 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Vigorous motion (jog) \r\n	-2 \r\n	-5 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Violent motion (run) \r\n	-4 \r\n	-10 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Very violent motion (sprint) \r\n	-6 \r\n	-15 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Environment 1  \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 - Blinding rain or sleet \r\n	-1 \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 - Wind-driven hail, dust, or debris \r\n	-2 \r\n	-5 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     1  Within each of these categories, apply only the highest absolute modifier.\r\n     2  Note that an entangled creature also suffers a Dex penalty that can further affect attack rolls.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Note that the Self-Control skill can be used to reduce PAM and MAM penalties.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Encumbrance Penalty (EP) \r\n     \r\n    Heavy equipment and armor increases a creature\'s \r\n    encumbrance class , \r\n    and this in turn leads to an\r\n    encumbrance penalty (EP) that applies to many physical actions, especially those related to movement.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When you are wearing armor with which you are non-proficient (skill level 0),\r\n    your EP also applies to all actions with the PAM modifier in the action check.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Synergy Bonus \r\n     \r\n    For some actions, proficiency in certain skills (other than the action\'s key skill, if any)\r\n    can be beneficial and provide a synergy bonus to the check.\r\n    Such synergy skills are listed under the modifiers for each action.\r\n    Multiple synergy bonuses do not stack; only the highest applicable one applies.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Defensive Action Checks \r\n     \r\n    Many actions tend to make you more vulnerable, triggering \r\n    attacks of opportunity  \r\n    (AoO) from opponents within reach.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, it is possible to perform those actions defensively, thereby avoiding AoO.\r\n    Performing an action defensively takes twice as long as normal (double the action time) and also involves a -4 circumstance penalty on the action check.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Opposing Action Checks \r\n     \r\n    Whenever two action checks are in opposition, the highest modified roll succeeds and the other fails.\r\n    In case of a tie, the highest modifier wins. If the modifiers are also the same, the result is a stalemate.\r\n    If a stalemate is not possible, even temporarily, reroll both checks until a winner can be determined.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In some cases, an action check will be opposed by several opposed checks.\r\n    For example, when you are sneaking, you want your stealth check to beat every opposed perception check.\r\n    In these situations, roll a single action check and compare it against each opposed check.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Linked Action Checks \r\n     \r\n    Some situations are complicated or long-lasting enough to require a sequence of action checks in order for the situation to be fully resolved.\r\n    These sequences of linked action checks are represented as a state diagram, where the change from one state to another is determined\r\n    by the success or failure of an action check.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A sequence of linked action checks always starts at a specific state, typically referred to as the initial state.\r\n    Each state has a specified duration, after which an action check is made to determine the new state in the sequence.\r\n    At least one state in a sequence is defined as a terminal state - when such a state has been reached,\r\n    the situation has been resolved and no further checks need to be made.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For a typical example of a state diagram for linked action checks, see Possession .\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Levels of Success and Failure \r\n     \r\n    In some cases, the degree of success or failure can be significant.\r\n    The difference between the total result and the target number is referred to as levels of success or failure.\r\n    For example, if the DC is 20 and you make a modified roll of 23, you have achieved 3 levels of success.\r\n    Sometimes this is also referred to as beating the DC by 3. For action checks where exceptional success or failure is possible,\r\n    the skill action will describe how many levels of success or failure are required to achieve such exceptional results.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    Some levels of success and failure are common enough to have their own standardized names:\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n   	Levels of Success/Failure \r\n     \r\n     Description \r\n     Levels of Success/Failure \r\n      \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Success (S) \r\n	 Success by 0 to 4 levels \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Outstanding Success (OS) \r\n	 Success by 5 to 9 levels \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Exceptional Success (ES) \r\n	 Success by 10 to 19 levels \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Critical Success (CS) \r\n	 Success by 20 or more levels \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Failure (F) \r\n	 Failure by 0 to 4 levels \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Outstanding Failure (OF) \r\n	 Failure by 5 to 9 levels \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Exceptional Failure (EF) \r\n	 Failure by 10 to 19 levels \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Critical Failure (CF) \r\n	 Failure by 20 or more levels \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n    Trying Again \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, actions can be retried indefinitely, regardless of success or failure.\r\n    However, note that each try takes the specified amount of time and carries the full cost.\r\n    In many cases, each failure will also have some sort of additional consequence.\r\n    Also note that actions that are reactions never allow more than one reactive action per triggering event.\r\n    There are even some actions where retrying is simply not possible, at least not until the situation has changed or your chances have improved.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For example, let us say you are trying to punch an opponent in the face. Regardless of whether the attack succeeds or fails,\r\n    you can usually try to punch him again. However, each attack takes a certain amount of time and effort,\r\n    and if your opponent runs away or manages to knock you unconscious, you can no longer retry your attack.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Taking 10 and Taking 20 \r\n     \r\n    During favorable conditions, it is possible to perform certain actions without rolling a d20.\r\n    &quot;Taking 10&quot; means that you perform the action in a relaxed and controlled manner,\r\n    and you simply replace the normal d20 roll with the value 10.\r\n    &quot;Taking 20&quot; means that you spend a lot of time getting a perfect result,\r\n    allowing you to replace the normal d20 roll with the value 20 (but without triggering an open-ended reroll).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In order to  &quot;take 10&quot; , the following prerequisites apply:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Your character must not be threatened, stressed, or distracted. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In order to  &quot;take 20&quot; , the following prerequisites apply:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Your character must not be threatened, stressed, or distracted. \r\n         The action must not carry penalties for failure. \r\n         The action must allow retries. \r\n         The action will take 20 times longer than normal to perform. \r\n         If materials are required and consumed, calculate the total cost as if 20 failures had been rolled. \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Taking 1 \r\n     \r\n    In situations where a creature is unable or unwilling to perform actions or roll active skill checks,\r\n    but where an action check is needed and an automatic failure is not appropriate,\r\n    determine the results as if the creature rolled a 1 (but without triggering an open-ended reroll).\r\n    This rule can be particularly useful for opposed action checks where one or both sides are passive.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Aiding Another \r\n     \r\n    In many cases, it is possible for multiple characters to cooperate when performing an action.\r\n    One of the characters (typically the one with the best chance) makes a normal action check against the appropriate target number.\r\n    Every cooperating character makes a similar action check against the target difficulty modified by -10,\r\n    and the first characterโs check receives a circumstance modifier for each supporting check.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Aid Another Results \r\n     \r\n     Aid Check Result \r\n    Circumstance Modifier \r\n      \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Success (S) \r\n	+2 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Outstanding Success (OS) \r\n	+4 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Exceptional Success (ES) \r\n	+6 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Critical Success (CS) \r\n	+10 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Failure (F) \r\n	0 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Outstanding Failure (OF) \r\n	-2 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Exceptional Failure (EF) \r\n	-4 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Critical Failure (CF) \r\n	-8 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Using a skill check to aid another takes the same amount of time, carries the same cost,\r\n    and provokes attacks of opportunity the same way that the base action check does.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The DM determines when aiding anotherโs action check is possible as well as the maximum number of beneficial helpers.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Cinematic Luck \r\n     \r\n     Cinematic Luck  (optional rule for more cinematic campaigns):\r\n    Heroes in movies and literature are often extremely lucky, even when those heroes are ordinary people.\r\n    If you want a similar effect in your campaign, consider allowing a certain number of action check rerolls\r\n    per day for each character. A reroll can also be used to force an opponent to reroll a successful attack.\r\n    Another option is to always let characters roll two d20 for each action check and use the highest roll.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Action Time \r\n     \r\n    Action time is the amount of time that must be spent to perform or at least initiate an action.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Action Time \r\n     \r\n     Time Unit \r\n    Abbr \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Weeks wks         For these long action times, full continuous concentration is neither possible nor required. If it is possible to spend part of the time on other activities, the percentage of time spent on the action is specified.   Days d           For these long action times, full continuous concentration is neither possible nor required. If it is possible to spend part of the time on other activities, the percentage of time spent on the action is specified.   Hours h           For these long action times, full continuous concentration is neither possible nor required. If it is possible to spend part of the time on other activities, the percentage of time spent on the action is specified.   Minutes min         The specified number of minutes must be spent to complete or initiate the action.   Rounds r           The specified number of complete rounds must be spent to complete or initiate the action. Partial rounds do not count. The action or effect takes place just before the start of your turn on the round after the specified number of rounds.   Full round r           A complete round (all AP and MP for the round) must be spent to complete or initiate the action. The action or effect takes place at the end of your current turn.   Partial round 1/4 r       It takes the specified fraction of a round to complete or initiate the action. Deduct the same fraction of the creature\'s action points and movement points (rounded up) for this round.   AP AP          The specified number of action points must be spent to complete or initiate the action.If you have an insufficient number of AP left of your turn, you can spend your remaining AP to initiate the action and pay the rest on your next turn. For many actions, interruption is then possible and may require skill checks to maintain concentration until the action is finished.   MP MP  The specified number of movement points must be spent to complete or initiate the action.If you have an insufficient number of MP left of your turn, you cannot initiate the action.   Reaction react  This means that the action can be performed as a reaction to another creature\'s action or some other triggering event. Unless otherwise specified, the reactive action is free and requires no AP to perform, but a creature can only perform one reactive action per triggering action.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Most variable decisions of an action, such as range, targets, area, etc., can be made at the end of the specified action time.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If the action time is longer than a full-round action and the action provokes attacks of opportunity,\r\n    it provokes new attacks of opportunity each round, at the beginning of your turn.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Whenever an action time specifies a percentage, it means that you can only work on the action efficiently for that portion of time.\r\n    The rest of the time is typically spent sleeping, relaxing, or performing unrelated actions.\r\n    On most of these actions you can also spend less than the specified portion of time, but this will increase the total action\r\n    time accordingly.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Implements \r\n     \r\n    An implement is a body part, tool, weapon, faculty, sense, etc. needed to perform the action.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Implements \r\n     \r\n     Implement \r\n    Abbr \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Concentration C           You need a certain amount of focus and concentration to perform the action. If you perform the action while you are already maintaining concentration on another action, you lose the earlier action.   Verbal V           You need to be able to speak in a firm voice. Typically, you have to use a language, but the targets (if any) do not need to understand the language. If you are deafened, you suffer a -4 circumstance penalty on the action check. Creatures without true languages (such as animals) cannot perform actions that require a verbal component.   Somatic S           You need to be able to gesticulate clearly with one or more hands; at least one hand must be empty and free to move. However, some actions allow special implements to be used in place of hands; for example, wands can be used for arcane spellcasting and holy symbols for divine spellcasting.If you use a hand-held implement for an action that has a range of Tch, you actually use the implement to make that touch. For small implements, like a wand or holy symbol, you still use Weapons - Natural for skill modifiers to the attack roll, but for larger implements, such as a staff, you instead use the appropriate Weapons skill. Note that magical implements will only provide their bonuses when the spell or power actually has a somatic component.   Material M           You need to use one or more consumables. The action\'s activation time assumes that the material is easy to reach (in a belt pouch, for instance, and not in a backpack). Otherwise, add the time required to find and retrieve the material.   Focus F           You need a catalyst that is not consumed by the action. The action\'s activation time assumes that the focus is easy to reach (in a belt pouch or around the neck, for instance, and not in a backpack).   Vision vis         You need eyes or an equivalent sense of vision. Vision-related modifiers may apply to the action.   Hearing aud         You need ears or an equivalent sense of hearing. Hearing-related modifiers may apply to the action.   Touch tch         You need a sense of touch.   Smell sml  You need a sense of smell.       \r\n \r\n\r\n    Action Cost \r\n     \r\n    The cost of an action includes all materials, money, stamina, blood, life energy, etc. that have to be spent in order to activate or complete the action.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Action Cost \r\n     \r\n     Cost Type \r\n    Abbr \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Wealth sp          The specified amount of coins or valuables has to be spent.   Health HP          The action requires a certain amount of blood or is otherwise injurious, measured as a HP cost.   Fatigue SP          The action is physically taxing and costs SP to perform.   Power PP          You become mentally fatigued when performing the action, expressed as a PP cost.   Experience XP          You have to spend a part of your soul and life energy to perform the action. This actually makes you forget a portion of your past life, and this in turn causes a reduction in XP (possibly even a reduction in level).As a slightly less drastic alternative to spending your own XP, you can use residuum (pure life energy and magic in a liquid form). Life energy can also sometimes be drawn from permanent magical devices, from creatures other than yourself, and from some very rare and expensive material components.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, the full cost has to be paid even if the check fails or the action is interrupted (voluntarily or involuntarily).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Whenever HP, SP, or PP are used to perform an action, those health points cannot be regained until the action or effect ends.\r\n    This effectively lowers the creature\'s maximum level of HP/SP/PP until the duration expires.\r\n    No form of natural or magical healing can restore the \"reserved\" HP/SP/PP until the effect has ended.\r\n    This also means that temporary HP, SP, and PP can only be used to pay the action cost for instantaneous actions.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    This rule applies to items as well as creatures, specifically when an item has a rechargeable or regenerating power pool.\r\n    For example, when a rechargeable wand creates a non-instantaneous effect,\r\n    its maximum PP will be reduced by the number of PP spent until the effect expires.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Range \r\n     \r\n    The range of an action is the greatest distance at which the actionโs effect can occur.\r\n    All targets or the point of origin of an area effect must be within this range.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Range \r\n     \r\n     Range \r\n    Abbr \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Personal pers        The action affects only you.   Touch tch         You must touch the target(s) of the action. Any natural weapon (hand, foot, claw, bite, etc.), even if covered with clothing or armor, can be used for the touch, and attack modifiers should be calculated as for a normal natural attack. Willing targets can be touched automatically, but unwilling targets require an unarmed attack roll. Thus, many actions with a range of touch require two checks, first one for the action itself and then one for the touch attack.Each willing target requires 2 AP to touch, while unwilling targets require an unarmed attack roll (costing 1 AP less than normal if you make a touch without causing natural weapon damage). Note however that, unless otherwise specified, the action time includes the time required for one basic touch attack (without the natural weapon damage), and that additional AP/MP can be spent on movement before the \"free\" touch. Note also that most touch effects take effect even if DR is not penetrated.Until the maximum number of targets have been touched, you have the option to maintain concentration between each touch attack and continue touching targets from round to round.Attacks delivered by touch can score a critical hit.Unless otherwise specified, when a touch attack is used to deliver an effect that normally targets Fort or Will, then the touch attack against DeC replaces the usual attack check, and skill modifiers for Weapons - Natural are used in place of Weapons - Body & Mind.   Reach rch         A melee weapon is used to deliver the action\'s effect, so any target must be within your weapon\'s reach. Attack modifiers should be calculated as for a normal attack with that weapon. Many actions with a range of reach require two checks, first one for the action itself and then one for the weapon attack.Unless otherwise specified, the action time includes the time required for the basic melee attack, and the action deals normal weapon damage in addition to the action\'s effect.Attacks delivered with a melee weapon can score a critical hit.   Ranged rng         The effect works similar to a ranged weapon and requires an attack roll against the DeC of each target (typically in addition to the action check itself).The specified range is actually a range increment, and each multiple incurs a cumulative -2 attack penalty. The maximum range is ten range increments, unless otherwise specified.   0 0           You are the effect\'s point of origin (but the area can still affect other targets).   Squares sq          The maximum range of the action\'s effect is the specified number of squares.   Close cls         The maximum range is equal to 5 + (skill level / 2) squares.   Medium mdm         The maximum range is equal to 20 + (skill level x 2) squares.   Long lng         The maximum range is equal to 80 + (skill level x 8) squares.   Infinite inf         The effect can reach anywhere within the same plane of existence.   Extraplanar ext         The effect can reach anywhere in any plane of existence.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Line of sight (LoS):  You must be able to see at least part of every target.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Line of hearing (LoH):  The target must be able to hear you clearly (and vice versa).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Line of effect (LoE):  You must have a straight and physically (but not necessarily visually) unobstructed path to the target(s).\r\n    Lines of effect can pass through openings as small as 30 cm in diameter.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Path of effect (PoE):  You must have a physically unobstructed (but not necessarily straight) path to the target(s).\r\n    Paths of effect can pass through openings as small as 30 cm in diameter.\r\n    A limited amount of obstructions can be penetrated but typically incur an action check penalty based on the material(s).\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, the range of an action is only significant during activation.\r\n    If the action\'s effect has a specified duration, the effect continues even if the targets move outside the specified range.\r\n    However, effects that can be redirected, dismissed, et. al. can only be thus affected while the controller is within range of the effect.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Duration \r\n     \r\n    Duration specifies how long an effect lasts.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Duration \r\n     \r\n     Duration \r\n    Abbr \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Years yrs         When the specified time expires, the effect ends.   Months mth         When the specified time expires, the effect ends.   Weeks wks         When the specified time expires, the effect ends.   Days d           When the specified time expires, the effect ends.   Hours h           When the specified time expires, the effect ends.   Minutes min         The effect ends after the specified number of minutes (multiply by 10 to get the number of rounds).   Rounds r           The effect ends after the specified number of full rounds. The effect ends at the same initiative count that it started, but at the end of the activator\'s turn.   Encounter enc         The effect ends when the current encounter ends. If this is used outside of an encounter, the duration is limited to approximately 1 minute per skill level.   Instantaneous instant     The actual effect lasts only an instant, but its consequences may be long-lasting or permanent.   Permanent perm        The effect has unlimited duration. If it is magical in nature, however, it can still be dispelled.   Concentration conc        The effect lasts for as long as concentration is maintained (and sometimes an additional specified duration after that).While concentrating, you can spend only half your AP and MP each round on other actions (and only on actions without the concentration implement).An action that triggers attacks of opportunity (AoO) will trigger another AoO at the beginning of each round of concentration. Every situation that can break your concentration will typically require a new skill check.An action that costs SP to initiate requires 1 SP per round of concentration, and an action that costs PP to initiate requires 1 PP per round of concentration.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Dismissible (D):  You can terminate a dismissible effect at will. However, this still requires a dismiss action, and you must be within the effectโs original range.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Area of Effect and Targets \r\n     \r\n    The area of effect of an action specifies the possible target(s), area, or general effect.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Areas of Effect \r\n     \r\n     Area of Effect / Target \r\n    Abbr \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n You you         The action affects only you.   Target tgt         Specifies the number and types of creatures or objects that can be affected.You typically need both line of sight and line of effect to each target (unless the range specifies otherwise). Selection of a target requires no aiming and no ranged attack roll, however, and the effect only has to overcome the defense and resistance of the target(s).Some actions can only affect willing targets, but unconscious creatures are automatically considered willing for such actions.   Ray ray         A ray is a ranged attack that can strike and affect a single creature or object.All of the modifiers and conditions that apply to ranged weapon attacks also apply to ray attacks.A ray is always instantaneous, and any other duration specified is the duration of the effect (not of the ray itself).Ray attacks can score critical hits.   Burst bst         The effect radiates the specified distance from the point of origin. It does not flow around corners, so a target\'s cover is calculated relative to the point of origin.A burst is always instantaneous, and any other duration specified is the duration of the effect (not of the burst itself).   Emanation emn         The effect radiates the specified distance from the point of origin, just like a burst effect.Emanations, however, are generally non-instantaneous and last for the action\'s specified duration.   Spread sprd        The effect spreads or flows out the specified distance from the point of origin. It can flow around corners, through openings, and into areas that you cannot see, but it does not penetrate solid obstructions.Spreads typically last for the action\'s specified duration.   Sphere sph         A spherical volume with the point of origin at its center.   Cone con         Has its apex at the point of origin and spreads in a 90 degree cone in any desired direction.   Cylinder cyl         A cylinder-shaped volume with its center at the point of origin. Many cylindrical volumes of effect have to be oriented with their circular surfaces parallel to the ground.   Line line        A narrow cylinder stretching away from the point of origin in any desired direction.       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Shapeable (S):  You can shape the area or volume within the specified limits.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When making an attack against multiple targets, a separate attack roll is made against each potential target.\r\n    In other words, it is possible for a single attack to fail against some targets, succeed against others, and even achieve critical success against some.\r\n    Damage, on the other hand, is typically rolled for only once and applied against all targets equally.\r\n    Note, however, that the degree of success and the defenses and resistances of each target can affect the actual damage inflicted.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When target specifies \"Ally\" or \"Allies\", this can also include you (unless otherwise specified).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n	In most cases, a target that is only partially within an area of effect will still be fully affected.\r\n	The DM is free to make exceptions to this rule when appropriate, maybe reducing the damage taken or giving a circumstance bonus to defenses.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For situations where exact placement of an area is difficult (due to poor visibility, long range, et al),\r\n    the DM should feel free to require an outstanding or even exceptional success for optimal placement.\r\n    A failure can be resolved by rolling 1d8 to determine an offset direction, and the offset distance should be 1%\r\n    of the desired range per level of failure.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Results and Effects \r\n     \r\n    Most offensive actions have to beat one or more of a targetโs defenses in order to have full effect.\r\n    In some cases, an attack can cause partial damage even when it fails to beat the targetโs defense.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, targets exposed to a hostile spell or action will be made aware of the attempt,\r\n    regardless of the result of the attack. However, the details of the attack and the identity of the attacker are not automatically revealed.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A target can willingly lower its defenses so that it is automatically (or at least more easily) affected by an attack.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Supernatural Actions and Power Level \r\n     \r\n    Just like supernatural creatures and objects, supernatural actions have a power level (PL).\r\n    The PL is used to determine the effectโs power against dispelling, magic resistance, anti-magic, and wild magic.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For spells and powers with a PP cost:  PL = Total PP cost + PP boost \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For other powers:  PL = skill level or creatureโs RL/TL \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When a supernatural effect has terminated, its magical aura will linger for a variable amount of time.\r\n    A PL of 1 to 5 lingers for 1d6 rounds, PL 6 to 10 for 1d6 minutes, PL 11 to 20 for 1d6&times;10 minutes, and PL 20+ for 1d6 days.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Modifiers \r\n     \r\n    Action checks (and other die rolls) are often affected by a variety of modifiers.\r\n    Positive modifiers are commonly referred to as bonuses and negative ones as penalties.\r\n    The following basic rules apply to modifiers:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Most modifiers belong to a specified type. \r\n         Modifiers of different types stack. \r\n         Modifiers without a specified type stack. \r\n         Modifiers of the same type do not normally stack. For each type, apply only the highest bonus and the most severe penalty. The following exceptions apply: \r\n         \r\n             Circumstance modifiers stack with circumstance modifiers from other sources. \r\n             Parry modifiers stack from all weapons and shields held in primary attack forms (typically hands). \r\n             Template modifiers stack with template modifiers from other compatible templates. \r\n             Improvement modifiers stack, but they have a limited total as described in the section about improvement points. \r\n             Inherent modifiers stack, but they are limited to a total of +5 for each ability score. \r\n         \r\n         Enhancement and material modifiers frequently apply to weapons, shields, armor, and other equipment rather than to a character or creature.\r\n        In this case, the modifier typically affects a property of the item (such as a weapon\'s attack modifier,\r\n        a shield\'s parry modifier, or an armor\'s DR) and only indirectly affects the item\'s user or wearer. \r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Modifier Types \r\n     \r\n     Modifier Type \r\n   	Abbreviation \r\n   	 Typical Source \r\n   	 Typically Affects \r\n   	  \r\n Ability Abl  Ability score (current and not base)  Defenses, action checks, damage rolls, init.   Age Age  Age  Ability scores, racial level, size   Armor Arm  Armor (artificial, not natural; can be enhanced)  Damage resistance   Circumstance Crc  Environment, cover, concealment, equipment, etc.  Action checks, defenses   Class Cls  Class or class specialization trait  Any   Cultural Clt  Upbringing  Skill levels, action checks   Deflection Dfl  Spell or magic item  DeC, Reflex defense   Divine Dvn  Divine magic  Any   Dodge Ddg  Skill or special ability  DeC, Reflex defense; Dodge can be a composite of multiple modifiers   Encumbrance Enc  Equipment, armor, obesity  Action checks, Dex bonus, base speed   Enhancement Enh  High quality or magic  Ability scores, weapon/armor effectiveness   Improvement Imp  Improvement points  Ability scores, health points, defenses, skill levels   Inherent Inh  Powerful and permanent magic  Ability scores   Insight Ins  Precognitive ability or magic  Defenses, action checks, damage rolls   Luck Lck  Unnaturally good or bad fortune  Defenses, action checks, damage rolls   Material Mat  Unusual material  Weapon/armor effectiveness   Metabolic Met  Drug, disease, poison, fatigue, etc.  Ability scores, base speed, defenses   Morale Mrl  Emotions  Will defense, action checks, damage rolls   Parry Par  Weapon or shield (can be enhanced)  DeC; Parry can be a composite of multiple modifiers   Racial Rac  Race or species (and gender)  Ability scores, defenses, skill levels, action checks   Resistance Res  Spell or magic item  Defenses   Size Siz  Size category  DeC, action checks   Skill Skl  Skill level  Defenses, attack rolls, damage rolls   Social Soc  Influence or reputation  Action checks   Synergy Syn  Skill level of 5 or better  Action checks   Template Tpl  Racial template  Ability scores, defenses, skill levels, action checks   Unnamed Nil  Any  Any   Weapon Wpn  Weapon or shield (can be enhanced)  Attack rolls, damage rolls       \r\n \r\n\r\n    Descriptors \r\n     \r\n    Descriptors are used to categorize a wide variety of things, including actions, spells, special abilities, objects, and creatures.\r\n    These descriptor categories can be used to determine whether a creatureโs resistance applies to a certain spell,\r\n    whether a certain action triggers attacks of opportunity or not, and much, much more.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Descriptors \r\n     \r\n     Descriptor \r\n   	 Notation \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Acid  [Acid]  Spell/action: causes acid energy damage (or protects against it).   Air  [Air]  Spell/action/creature: related to the air element.   Aquatic  [Aquatic]  Creature: has native swim speed and does not have to make Athletics (Swim) checks to move through water; can breathe underwater.   Attack of Opportunity  [AoO]  Action: using this action triggers attacks of opportunity from creatures that threaten you.   Augmented  [Augmented]  Creature: augmented with a template or special power.   Boost  [Boost]  Action: a supernatural action that can be boosted with an additional investment of PP. It can be boosted by up to your skill level (if not applicable, use TL) PP. The boost increases the power\'s PL, and it serves as an action check bonus (but never as an attack check bonus). Alternatively, the action can be dampened by up to the same amount of PP. Dampening adds to the PP cost same as boosting, but it decreases the PL and serves as an action check penalty.   Chaotic  [Chaotic]  Creature/weapon/spell/trait: has a chaotic aura and can bypass DR susceptible to chaotic.   Charm  [Charm]  Spell/action: causes a charm effect.   Cold  [Cold]  Spell/action: causes cold energy damage (or protects against it).Creature: immune to cold and vulnerable to fire.   Darkness  [Dark]  Spell/action: creates a darkness or shadow effect.   Dimension  [Dimension]  Spell/action: creates or uses an extradimensional or extraplanar effect.   Earth  [Earth]  Spell/action/creature: related to the earth element.   Electricity  [Electric]  Spell/action: causes electrical energy damage (or protects against it).   Evil  [Evil]  Creature/weapon/spell/trait: has an evil aura and can bypass DR susceptible to evil.   Fear  [Fear]  Spell/action/trait: causes a fear effect.   Fire  [Fire]  Spell/action: causes fire energy damage (or protects against it), or is related to the fire element.Creature: immune to fire/heat and vulnerable to cold.   Force  [Force]  Spell/action: causes force damage (usually blunt physical damage) or creates a telekinetic effect.   Good  [Good]  Creature/weapon/spell/trait: has a good aura and can bypass DR susceptible to good.   Illusion  [Illusion]  Spell/action: creates an illusionary effect.   Incorporeal  [Incorporeal]  Spell/action: makes a target incorporeal.Creature: is or can become incorporeal.   Language-dependent  [Lang]  Spell/action: works only if the user and target can communicate with a shared language.   Lawful  [Lawful]  Creature/weapon/spell/trait: has a lawful aura and can bypass DR susceptible to lawful.   Light  [Light]  Spell/action: creates a light or color-based effect.   Magic Resistance  [MR]  Spell/action: supernatural effect that is susceptible to a target\'s magic resistance.   Mind-affecting  [Mind]  Spell/action: causes a mental effect. It does not work against creatures with Int 0 or Int -.   Move  [Move]  Action: a movement action that requires MP (or AP converted to MP).   Necrotic  [Necrotic]  Spell/action: causes necrotic energy damage (or protects against it).   Poison  [Poison]  Spell/action/weapon: is poisonous or creates a toxic effect.   Radiant  [Radiant]  Spell/action: causes radiant energy damage, protects against radiant energy, or uses radiant energy for healing.   Secret  [Secret]  Action: the DM should (usually) make a hidden roll for the character.   Sleep  [Sleep]  Spell/action: causes a sleep effect.   Sonic  [Sonic]  Spell/action: causes sonic energy damage (or protects against it).   Supernatural  [Su]  Action/trait: subject to anti-magic, dispelling, and counterspelling. Effects that are not supernatural may be exceptional in many ways, but they are not magical and therefore not subject to anti-magic or dispelling.   Take 10/20  [T10/20]  Action: an action check that you can \"take 10\" and/or \"take 20\" on.   Telepathy  [Telepathy]  Spell/action/trait: causes a telepathic effect or uses telepathy.   Teleport  [Teleport]  Spell/action: uses a teleportation effect.   Turning  [Turn]  Spell/action: supernatural effect very similar to fear but unaffected by resistance to mind and fear effects.   Untrained  [Untrained]  Action: can be attempted even by a creature with no levels in the appropriate skill.   Water  [Water]  Spell/action/creature: related to the water element.       \r\n \r\n\r\n    Prerequisites \r\n     \r\n    Prerequisites are conditions that need to be satisfied within the given context.\r\n    Prerequisites can be applied to almost anything, including skills, classes, bonuses, magic items, etc.\r\n    For example, skill A can have a prerequisite stating that skill B must be learned to a certain level before you can allocate skill points to skill A.\r\n    Another example is a bonus that only applies when you are wearing a certain type of armor or wielding a certain type of weapon.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In most cases, prerequisites are self-explanatory and simple to resolve, but there are exceptions.\r\n    For example, when you are levelling up a character, improvement points may be used before resolving prerequisites for skills.\r\n    However, allocation of skill points when levelling up is effectively done at a single point in time.\r\n    This means that skills gained or improved when levelling may not count their improved level to fulfill prerequisites for another skill (until after the levelling).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Sometimes, a prerequisite can be temporarily satisfied due to a bonus of limited duration.\r\n    The opposite situation is also possible, where a temporary penalty results in a prerequisite no longer being satisfied.\r\n    The default rule is to use a creature\'s current characteristics to resolve any prerequisite.\r\n    For example, if a magic hammer requires a minimum strength of 18 and your normal strength is 16,\r\n    you can hypothetically use a magic spell to increase your strength and successfully wield the hammer.\r\n    Conversely, if your strength normally is 20 but has been reduced to 17 by a spider\'s venomous bite,\r\n    then you are temporarily unable to wield the aforementioned hammer.\r\n    For the purpose of resolving \"long-term\" prerequisites, such as skill prerequisites and actions with a long action time,\r\n    you should only count bonuses and penalties that have a duration at least as long as the action time.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Prerequisites are typically expressed as logical expressions that can be evaluated to true or false.\r\n    Most prerequisites are simple expressions with a single condition, but it is possible to combine multiple conditions\r\n    with the logical operators \'AND\', \'OR\', and \'XOR\'.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    	\r\n    \r\n   	Prerequisite Types \r\n     \r\n     Prerequisite Type \r\n     Example \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Ability Score  Str>=15 AND Con>=12  The specified ability scores must have at least the specified values.   Alignment  Align==G  Alignment must be lawful good, neutral good, or chaotic good.   Armor  Armor==ArmMd  Armor being worn must be medium type armor.   Casting  Casting(music)  Musical instrument must be used as somatic component and singing as verbal component.   Challenge Level  CL=10  Class level for the wizard class must be 10 or better.   Condition  Cond(Bloodied)  Must have the bloodied condition.   Creature Subtype  CrSubt==Elf  Must belong to the elven creature subtype.   Creature Type  CrType==Humanoid  Must belong to the humanoid creature type.   Descriptor  Desc(Fire) OR Desc(Cold)  Must have the Fire descriptor and/or the Cold descriptor.   Encumbrance Class  EC=5  Racial level must be 5 or better.   Size  Sz=8  Skill level in Acrobatics skill must be 8 or better.   Social Class  SC>=2  Social class must be 2 or better.   Total Level  TL==8  Total level must be exactly 8.   Wealth Class  WC','2013-01-26',255.5,'b40a8c3ac04a78a07cb27ed23e0ee9ed',0,1),(73,2,'http://localhost/rold20/analysis.php','RoL d20 - Analysis','','\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n	\r\n\r\n		\r\n	            \r\n	             \r\n	            \r\n	                 \r\n	                    RoL d20 Role-Playing System\r\n	                 \r\n	 