ies \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Character Generation \r\n     \r\n    When generating a player character, use the following steps:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Choose a basic character concept, including class or at least a type of class. You should also give some thoughts to race and gender. \r\n         Roll for base ability scores according to DM guidelines. Six ability scores in the 3-18 range should be generated. \r\n         Choose race and gender. You may also choose a culture separately from race, if the DM allows it. \r\n         Choose or roll for age. \r\n         Assign and calculate ability scores (base ability + racial adj + age adj). Note that if a PC gets an adjusted Int below 3, set it to 3 instead.\r\n        Any ability score that gets an adjusted value below 1 should be set to 1. Calculate ability modifiers. \r\n         Choose class. \r\n         Record racial special traits. \r\n         Record class special traits. \r\n         Generate and record derived numbers: \r\n         \r\n             Hit Points, Stamina Points, and Power Points. \r\n             Initiative Modifier. \r\n             Defense Class. \r\n             Fortitude, Reflex, and Will Defenses. \r\n             Attack Modifiers. \r\n             Encumbrance Class and Penalty. \r\n             Fate Points. \r\n         \r\n         Learn skills by distributing skill points. For background skills, choose one of your culture\'s background classes. \r\n         Choose or generate physical appearance. \r\n         Choose or generate personality characteristics. \r\n         Roll for wealth and buy equipment. \r\n         Choose spells known. \r\n         Update characteristics based on skills and equipment. \r\n         Choose or generate a name. \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Ability Score Generation \r\n     \r\n    Generate \r\n    base ability scores  \r\n    using one of the following methods (subject to the DMโs approval):\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	    \r\n   	Ability Generation Methods - Elite \r\n     \r\n     Generation Method \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Method E-I  Roll 4d6 and discard the lowest die. Do this six times. Assign each score to one base ability.   Method E-II  You have 25 points with which to buy your base ability scores. See the table below for point costs.   Method E-III  Assign the following scores as desired: 15, 14, 13, 12, 10, and 8.   Method E-IV  Same as method I, but a single score can be rerolled once during the process.   Method E-V  Roll 4d6 and discard the lowest die. Do this six times and assign in order to Str, Con, Dex, Int, Wis, and Cha. Reroll any one ability score of your choice, and take the new roll if it is higher. Finally, you may switch any two ability scores.   E-Rerolling  Regardless of method, if the sum of your ability modifiers is 0 or less, or your highest score is 13 or lower, you are recommended to start over and reroll all ability scores.       \r\n    \r\n   	Ability Generation Methods - Average \r\n     \r\n     Generation Method \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Method A-I  Roll 3d6. Do this six times. Assign each score to one base ability.   Method A-II  You have 15 points with which to buy your ability scores. See the table below for point costs.   Method A-III  Assign the following scores as desired: 13, 12, 11, 10, 9, and 8.   Method A-IV  Assign the following scores as desired: 11, 11, 11, 10, 10, and 10.       \r\n    \r\n   	Ability Generation Methods - Heroic \r\n     \r\n     Generation Method \r\n   	 Description \r\n   	  \r\n Method H-I  Roll 5d6 (or even 6d6) and total the three highest. Do this six times. Assign each score to one base ability.   Method H-II  You have 35 (or even 40) points with which to buy your base ability scores. See the table below for point costs.   Method H-III  Assign the following scores as desired: 18, 15, 13, 12, 10, and 8.   Method H-IV  Same as method I, but a single score can be rerolled once during the process.   Method H-V  Roll 5d6 (or even 6d6) and total the three highest dice. Do this six times and assign in order to Str, Con, Dex, Int, Wis, and Cha. Reroll any one ability score of your choice, and take the new roll if it is higher. Finally, you may switch any two ability scores.   Method H-VI  Assign the following dice pools to one ability score each: 9d6, 8d6, 7d6, 5d6, 4d6, 3d6. Roll the indicated number of dice and add the three highest dice in each pool. The six results are your scores.   H-Rerolling  Regardless of method, if the sum of your ability modifiers is +3 or less, or your highest score is 15 or lower, you are recommended to start over and reroll all ability scores.       \r\n    \r\n   	Ability Point Buy System \r\n     \r\n    Ability Score \r\n   	Point Cost \r\n   	  \r\n3 -5  4 -4  5 -3  6 -2  7 -1  8 0  9 1  10 2  11 3  12 4  13 5  14 6  15 8  16 10  17 13  18 16       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Average Characters  (optional rule for more realistic campaigns):\r\n    Use one of the average ability generation methods listed above.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Heroic Characters  (optional rule for more cinematic campaigns):\r\n    Use one of the heroic ability generation methods listed above.\r\n     \r\n    \r\n    Character Races \r\n     \r\n    This chapter lists the races (i.e. species) most commonly available for player characters.\r\n    It is merely a subset of the larger number of creatures described in the \r\n    creature chapter , \r\n    and some of those may also be suitable for characters\r\n    (at the DMโs discretion). Note, however, that this chapter and the original D&amp;D rules provide more role-playing information than\r\n    is available for most non-character creatures.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In addition to the base races, you can apply one of the listed templates to a base race,\r\n    but note that most templates have a CL modifier and may not be allowed for low-level campaigns.\r\n    Most of the templates represent an unusual bloodline somewhere among oneโs ancestors.\r\n    For example, your character can be a half-dragon human, a human with draconic blood, also known as a dragonborn.\r\n    Or you can be a half-earth elemental gnome, sometimes known as an earth genasi. Although many of the templates are referred to as half-something,\r\n    the unusual ancestry is often more distant in the family tree than one of your parents. Also note that some human-based hybrids,\r\n    notably half-elves and half-orcs, are common and distinct enough to be listed as separate races in their own right.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    With very few exceptions, the &quot;non-technical&quot; details listed for character races in D&amp;D still apply.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, personality, physical description, relations with other races, alignment, culture, and religion are the same as in the original rules.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The racial traits make a distinction between true racial traits and cultural traits.\r\n    The true racial traits are genetically and inherently a part of that race,\r\n    while the cultural traits apply only to individuals that grew up in a family or society of the specified race.\r\n    For example, an elf that grew up among other elves will have both racial and cultural traits typical for elves.\r\n    On the other hand, an elf that is raised by dwarves should have the racial traits of an elf but at least some of the dwarven cultural traits (instead of the elven ones).\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n     Type and subtype:  Racial types and subtypes are described in the creature chapter.\r\n     Ability Adjustment:  Racial ability score adjustments.\r\n     RL:  The racial level of an adult member of the race. Most player character races have RL 0.\r\n     CL:  If the race has characteristics that make it more powerful than a typical human, this is expressed as a positive CL modifier (an effective level increase). The DM may disallow such races for player characters.\r\n     Size Class:  Size category for an adult member of the race.\r\n     Average Size:  Average height/length (in cm) for adult males and females, respectively.\r\n     Average Weight:  Average weight (in kg) for adult males and females, respectively. \r\n     Age Categories:  Age categories (in years) for mature, old, and venerable.\r\n     Base Speed:  Base speed for ground, swim, and fly movement modes (in squares).\r\n     DR/MR:  Natural damage resistance and base magic resistance (if any).\r\n     Body Type:  Body category.\r\n     Natural Attacks:  List of natural attacks and their default weapon statistics.\r\n     Alignment:  This is the overall moral tendency for the race as a whole.\r\n     Racial Traits:  Special traits and bonuses due to race.\r\n     Default Culture:  Default culture. Also specifies the class equivalences typically used for background skills.\r\n     Cultural Traits:  Special traits and bonuses granted by the default culture.\r\n     \r\n Dwarf, Gray (Duergar)    Type and Subtype:  Humanoid (Dwarf)   Ability Adjustments:  Con +2, Wis +2, Cha -4   RL / CL:  0 / +1   Size Class:  Medium   Average Size (M/F):  127 / 122   Average Weight (M/F):  61 / 48   Age Categories (M/O/V):  125 / 188 / 250   Base Speed (G/S/F):  4 / - / -   Body Type:  Biped   Natural Attacks:  2 Arm (Prim; Sz: -3; AP: 5; A/P: DexMod/0; Dmg d3+StrMod B SP; Rch 0-1; Can\'t be disarmed)2 Leg (Sec; Sz: -2; AP: 6; A/P: DexMod-1/0; Dmg d4+StrMod B SP; Rch 0-1; Can\'t be disarmed)1 Head (Sec; Sz: -2; AP: 6; A/P: DexMod-1/0; Dmg d3+StrMod/2 B SP; Rch 0-0; Can\'t be disarmed)   Appearance:  Light or dark gray skin.Bald (both male and female); nearly all men grow long gray facial hair.Dark (brown or black) eyes.   Personality:  Most are sullen, suspicious, greedy, evil, and bitter. On the positive side, they are courageous soldiers and tireless workers.   Align