 	 Primary Skills: \r\n		   	 WpGen, WpClb, WpCrs, ArmLt, ArmMd \r\n		   	 \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Secondary Skills: \r\n		   	 Percp, Ride, WpLtB, WpPlA, WpShd, CmbIn \r\n		   	 \r\n		     \r\n		    \r\n		    \r\n		     \r\n		     Warrior Configuration: \r\n		   	 Savage \r\n		   	  \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Primary Skills: \r\n		   	 Athle, WpAxe, WpGen, WpClb, WpBow, WpSmT, ArmLt, CmbIn \r\n		   	 \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Secondary Skills: \r\n		   	 Percp, Ride, Steal, Surv, WpShd, FSBrl \r\n		   	 \r\n		     \r\n		    \r\n		    \r\n		     \r\n		     Warrior Configuration: \r\n		   	 Spearman \r\n		   	  \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Primary Skills: \r\n		   	 WpGen, WpSpr, WpCrs, ArmLt, ArmMd \r\n		   	 \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Secondary Skills: \r\n		   	 Percp, Ride, WpLtB, WpPlA, WpShd, CmbIn \r\n		   	 \r\n		     \r\n		    \r\n		    \r\n		     \r\n		     Warrior Configuration: \r\n		   	 Swordsman \r\n		   	  \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Primary Skills: \r\n		   	 WpGen, WpHvB, WpCrs, ArmLt, ArmMd \r\n		   	 \r\n		   	\r\n		   	 Secondary Skills: \r\n		   	 Percp, Ride, WpLtB, WpPlA, WpShd, CmbIn \r\n		   	 \r\n		     \r\n \r\n\r\n    Multi-Classing \r\n     \r\n    As a character progresses in level, he or she can either focus on a single class or mix multiple classes.\r\n    Note that entering a new class is subject to the DMโs approval and also requires meeting any prerequisites of the new class.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Skills \r\n\r\n     Acquiring Skills \r\n     \r\n    Characters gain skill points as they increase in level, and those skill points can be used to buy levels in a wide variety of \r\n    skills .\r\n    Each skill point is worth one skill level. For each increase in TL (i.e. racial level or class level),\r\n    a character can spend 0, 0.5, or 1 skill points on primary skills and 0 or 0.5 skill points on secondary skills.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Some skills provide a number of specializations, and these specializations cost additional skill points.\r\n    Each specialization costs 1 skill point, but this cost does not count against the number of skill points that can be spent per skill and level.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Background Skills \r\n     \r\n    Player characters (and most other creatures) acquire some skills before they even start their class training.\r\n    Each culture has one or more class equivalences, and an adult member of that culture receives background skill points\r\n    as if it had (RL + 1) levels in one of those classes.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Optional Skill Rules \r\n     \r\n     Out-of-Class Skill Access  (optional rule for more varied characters):\r\n    Each character can choose one skill that he always has primary access to, regardless of class choice.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Retraining  (optional rule for simpler character generation):\r\n    Each character can redistribute (effectively retrain) a certain number (DM\'s choice) of previously earned skill points at each level.\r\n    This is in addition to and separate from the skill points normally used to improve or learn new skills.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Skill points can be moved from any skill, but no more than 1 point can be moved per skill and level. \r\n         The moved skill points can be assigned according to the skills available to the levelled class.\r\n        Primary skills can be increased by 0.5 or 1 points, while secondary skills can only be increased by 0.5 points.\r\n        As noted above, this is in addition to the regular skill training. \r\n         The maximum number of total skill points that may be allocated to any skill is (TL + 1). \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Other Characteristics \r\n\r\n     Health Scores \r\n     \r\n    Calculate HP, SP, and PP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     HP = Con + (HP bonus per class and level) + (HP bonus per race and level) &times; size factor \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     SP = Con + (SP bonus per class/race and level) \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     PP = Wis + (PP bonus per class/race and level) \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Defense Scores \r\n     \r\n    Calculate DeC, Fort, Ref, and Will.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     DeC (passive) = 10 + size mod + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     DeC (active) = DeC (passive) + Dex mod + parry bonus + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Fort = 10 + Str mod + Con mod + TL + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Ref = 10 + Dex mod + Int mod + TL + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Will = 10 + Wis mod + Cha mod + TL + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Resistance Scores \r\n     \r\n    Unless a characterโs race states otherwise, the character starts with damage resistance, energy resistance, and magic resistance at 0.\r\n    Equipment and magic can be used to improve these resistances later on.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Initiative Modifier \r\n     \r\n     Init = Dex mod + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Social Scores \r\n     \r\n    Characters start at social class 0 and wealth class 0. The DM may allow other starting values under special circumstances.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     SC = 0 \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     WC = 0 \r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Infl = Cha + (Infl bonus per class/race and level) + SC bonus + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The player should choose the focus of his characterโs influence, but this choice is subject to DM approval.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Rep = TL + SC + WC + other modifiers \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The player should choose the nature of his characterโs reputation, but this choice is subject to DM approval.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Action Points \r\n     \r\n     AP = 10 + TL (unless otherwise specified for the characterโs race) \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Fate Points \r\n     \r\n    Player characters start the game with 3 fate points.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Appearance \r\n     \r\n    Choose (or randomly generate) the characterโs appearance, based on the physical description of the characterโs race. Consider at least the following aspects:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Height and weight \r\n         \r\n             For random height, multiply average height by (75+5d10)% (in other words, 80% to 125% of average). \r\n             For random weight, multiply average weight by (height multiplier)ร(75+5d10)%. \r\n         \r\n         Skin (or fur) color \r\n         Eye color \r\n         Hair color and hairstyle \r\n         Facial hair \r\n         Distinguishing marks \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Personality \r\n     \r\n    Alignment is no longer a PC characteristic as such. The player should choose a personality for his or her character and act accordingly.\r\n    The DM will observe a characterโs actions and may use this to maintain a secret alignment evaluation\r\n    (for the purposes of detection spells, class restrictions, items limited to certain alignments, etc).\r\n    If the character wants to find out about his alignment, asking the DM is not the way to do it;\r\n    he or she will have to find and ask a trustworthy cleric. The cleric may even be able to explain why the character has that alignment,\r\n    but this explanation will be from the clericโs point of view, of course.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The player is recommended to describe his characterโs personality with a few keywords.\r\n    A couple of unusual mannerisms can also make a character more fun to play and more memorable for all involved.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Name \r\n     \r\n    Choose (or randomly generate) a name that you feel is appropriate to the characterโs race and culture.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Background and Relationships \r\n     \r\n    Choose (or randomly generate) a background story for your character. Try to consider at least the following aspects:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         History and upbringing \r\n         Family and relatives \r\n         Friends and foes \r\n         Reasons for choosing class and skills \r\n         Reasons for becoming an adventurer \r\n         Best and worst things that ever happened \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Experience and Level \r\n     \r\n    In most campaigns, each player character starts at level 1 and with 0 XP.\r\n    Unless the DM says otherwise, this means that races and templates with RL and/or CL modifier higher than 0 are not allowed as player character races.\r\n    Likewise, starting at a SC or WC above 0 may not be allowed.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    In campaigns that start at a higher level than 1, the DM should let the players know how many XP their characters have to start with.\r\n    The players can themselves choose how to divide their total level between different classes.\r\n    They may also be allowed to choose races that have racial levels and/or CL modifiers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    As a character adventures, he will earn more XP by overcoming enemies, obstacles, and challenges.\r\n    When enough experience has been earned, the character attains a new level. When this happens, follow these steps:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Choose a class in which to advance, either one already possessed or a new one. This class level increases by one. \r\n         Alternatively, if the character belongs to a race with racial levels and the maximum racial level has not yet been reached, feel free to increase the racial level instead of a class level. \r\n         Increase HP, SP, and PP according to the new level. \r\n         Increase Infl according to the new level and increase Rep by 1. \r\n         Increase your AP total by 1. \r\n         You gain skill points according to the new level. Use them to gain new or improve old skills. \r\n         \r\n             Each primary skill of the chosen class can be improved by 0, 0.5, or 1 skill point. \r\n             Each secondary skill of the chosen class can be improved by 0 or 0.5 skill points. \r\n             Any primary or secondary skill specialization can be bought (or improved) for 1 skill point. \r\n             Skill points have to be spent; they cannot be saved for future use. \r\n         \r\n         You may use improvement points (new and/or saved ones) to improve your character. \r\n         Note any new class traits provided by the level. \r\n         Recalculate any characteristics that are dependent on level or skill improvements. \r\n         \r\n             Defenses. \r\n             Attack and damage bonuses. \r\n         \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The character is assumed to spend time between adventures training and studying, automatically learning how to use his new abilities and skills.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     Level Training  (optional rule for more realistic campaigns):\r\n    Instead of automatically granting a new level whenever a character accumulates sufficient XP,\r\n    a certain amount of time (x days, weeks, or even months) needs to be spent training and studying.\r\n    Optionally, the assistance of a teacher or master may also be required (and somehow paid for).\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Starting Wealth \r\n     \r\n    When starting at 1st level, each character has 4d6ร10 sp with which to buy \r\n    weapons, armor, and other equipment .\r\n    In addition, he automatically starts with one set of basic clothing (worth up to 5 sp).\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	\r\n	 \r\n    Recommended wealth per level:\r\n     \r\n\r\n    \r\n   	Wealth per Level \r\n     \r\n    Level \r\n   	PC Wealth (sp) \r\n   	NPC Wealth (sp) \r\n   	  \r\n1 125 900  2 900 2000  3 2700 2500  4 5400 3300  5 9000 4300  6 13000 5600  7 19000 7200  8 27000 9400  9 36000 12000  10 49000 16000  11 66000 21000  12 88000 27000  13 110000 35000  14 150000 45000  15 200000 59000  16 260000 77000  17 340000 100000  18 440000 130000  19 580000 170000  20 760000 220000  21 975000 280000  22 1200000 350000  23 1500000 430000  24 1800000 520000  25 2100000 620000  26 2500000 730000  27 2900000 850000  28 3300000 980000  29 3800000 1120000  30 4300000 1270000       \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    New characters above 1st level should not be allowed items worth more than 25% of their total wealth.\r\n     \r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n		     \r\n         \r\n\r\n		\r\n         \r\n        \r\n            \r\n          \r\n		\r\n     \r\n \r\n ','2013-01-26',159.85,'edce7944b601e44c3aefc6e66659bbaf',0,2),(75,2,'http://localhost/rold20/hb04_combat.php','RoL d20 - Rules of Combat','','\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n	\r\n\r\n		\r\n	            \r\n	             \r\n	            \r\n	                 \r\n	                    RoL d20 Role-Playing System\r\n	                 \r\n	             \r\n			  \r\n		\r\n        \r\n			\r\n		 Handbook \r\n         \r\n             Introduction  \r\n             Core Mechanics  \r\n             \r\n                 Characteristics  \r\n                 Action Checks  \r\n                 Modifiers  \r\n                 Descriptors  \r\n                 Prerequisites  \r\n                 Conditions  \r\n                 Special Senses  \r\n                 Special Abilities  \r\n             \r\n             Character Generation  \r\n             \r\n                 Ability Scores  \r\n                 Character Races  \r\n                 Character Classes  \r\n                 Other Characteristics  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Combat  \r\n             \r\n                 Combat Sequence  \r\n                 Action Points  \r\n                 Combat Modifiers  \r\n                 Attack Types  \r\n                 Damage Types  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Magic  \r\n             \r\n                 Casting Spells  \r\n                 Learning Spells  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Environment  \r\n             \r\n                 Movement  \r\n                 Environment  \r\n                 The Multiverse  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Culture  \r\n             Rules of Engagement  \r\n             \r\n                 Encounters  \r\n                 Experience  \r\n                 Treasure  \r\n             \r\n             List of Skills  \r\n             \r\n                 Skill Availability  \r\n                 Skill Descriptions  \r\n             \r\n             List of Actions  \r\n             List of Spells  \r\n             List of Equipment  \r\n             \r\n	             Mundane Items  \r\n	             Complex Items  \r\n	             Item Modifications  \r\n	             Materials  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Creatures  \r\n             \r\n	             Aberrations  \r\n	             Animals  \r\n	             Monstrous Animals  \r\n	             Constructs  \r\n	             Dragons  \r\n	             Elementals  \r\n	             Humanoids  \r\n	             Monstrous Humanoids  \r\n	             Outsiders  \r\n	             Plants &amp; Fungi  \r\n	             Undead  \r\n	             Templates  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Cultures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Rules of Combat \r\n\r\n    Encounter and Combat Sequence \r\n     \r\n         Determine surprise situation and encounter distance. \r\n         All combatants start out flat-footed. Once a combatant gets to act, he is no longer flat-footed. \r\n         Roll for initiative. \r\n         Combatants who are not surprised act in order of initiative. \r\n         During each of the following rounds, all combatants act in order of initiative. For each combatant... \r\n         \r\n             Update health points based on continuous damage, regeneration, etc. \r\n             Assign AP to initial defense bonus. \r\n             Use the remaining AP and MP to perform actions (or increase your defense bonus).\r\n            Whenever an attack action is performed, additional AP can be spent on attack and/or damage bonuses. \r\n         \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Encounters and Surprise \r\n     \r\n    An encounter starts whenever one group becomes aware of another (or both groups become aware simultaneously).\r\n    Initial encounter distance between the two groups usually depends on terrain, environment, lines of sight, and Perception checks.\r\n    Surprise and initiative can be useful to determine the starting situation and positions, regardless of whether the encounter turns into combat or not.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Every encounter starts with a special round known as a surprise round. This round is just half as long as a regular round,\r\n    and only the participants that are aware of the situation (typically through a successful Perception check) get to act during this round.\r\n    All other participants are surprised, flat-footed, and unable to act. Since the surprise round is half the length of a normal round,\r\n    full-round actions are not possible, and each participant can only use half the normal number of action points and movement points.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Every participant in an encounter starts out flat-footed, and he remains flat-footed until his first action.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Initiative \r\n     \r\n    Participants in an encounter act in order of initiative (highest to lowest), as determined by initiative checks at the start of the encounter.\r\n    If two or more participants get the same initiative result, they act in order of initiative modifier (highest to lowest).\r\n    The same order is repeated each round, unless the actions of a participant changes his position in the sequence.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Initiative check:  d20 + Dex mod + other mods\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When new participants join an ongoing encounter, they enter the action โbetween roundsโ.\r\n    If the newcomers are aware of the encounter before joining it, they automatically act before anyone else in the next round.\r\n    Their initiative is set to 1 higher than the previously highest initiative.\r\n    Newcomers that are not aware of the encounter beforehand roll for initiative normally and are flat-footed until their first action.\r\n    In other words, the original participants may be able to attack the newcomers before they get a chance to act.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    At the beginning of a creatureโs turn, update health points for continuous damage effects, \r\n    regeneration , \r\n    and similar effects.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Creatures that have a close connection or bond to another creature, including mounts, pets, familiars, companions, servants, and cohorts,\r\n    should normally not roll for individual initiative. In the presence of their rider or master,\r\n    they should always act on the masterโs initiative (but after the master).\r\n    If the creature in question has a better initiative modifier than the master, the creatureโs presence gives the master a +1 circumstance bonus to initiative.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Movement Points \r\n     \r\n    During each round, a creature gets a number of \r\n    movement points  (MP)\r\n    equal to its adjusted speed characteristic (for the appropriate mode of movement).\r\n    MP can be used for movement actions at any time during the creature\'s turn, but they cannot be used as a reaction.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A creature can have several modes of movement with different adjusted speeds.\r\n	If this is the case, different modes of movement can be used in a single round,\r\n	but the available amount of MP is limited by the lowest adjusted speed out of the modes used.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Movement points that have been allocated or spent will not be regained until your next round.\r\n    Points that are still unused at the end of your turn provide no special bonuses.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Action Points \r\n     \r\n    Every creature has a certain number of \r\n    action points  (AP). \r\n    During each round, the creature can use its action points to focus on precision attacks, damage, defense, and/or more actions.\r\n    All action points do not have to be allocated from the beginning of your turn, nor do actions have to be declared from the beginning.\r\n    It is possible to first make one attack with additional AP spent on an attack bonus,\r\n    then decide to allocate AP to a defense bonus (lasting until the beginning of your next turn),\r\n    and finally make a second attack with the remaining AP spent on increased damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Points that have been allocated or spent will not be regained until your next round,\r\n    but unspent points can be used for any purpose at any point during your turn.\r\n    But note that action points can only be allocated when initiating an action and never during an action.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    You do not have to spend all your AP during your turn.\r\n    Unspent points can be used to gain bonuses for attacks of opportunity or other reactive actions that occur before the beginning of your next turn.\r\n     \r\n    \r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    The following table lists the things you can do with action points:\r\n     \r\n    \r\n	\r\n   	Action Point Bonuses \r\n     \r\n     Benefit \r\n    Abbr. \r\n    AP Cost \r\n     Description \r\n      \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Attack Bonus \r\n	AB \r\n	1 per +1 \r\n	 You make a precision attack. For the next attack action, you gain the indicated bonus on all attack rolls.\r\n	You can spend a maximum of half your AP on AB for a single action. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Damage Bonus \r\n	DaB \r\n	1 per +1 \r\n	 You make a powerful attack. For the next attack action, you gain the indicated damage bonus on all weapon attacks.\r\n	You can spend a maximum of half your AP on DaB for a single action. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Defense Bonus \r\n	DeB \r\n	1 per +1 \r\n	 You focus on parrying and dodging. Until the beginning of your next turn, you gain the indicated bonus to DeC.\r\n	You can spend a maximum of half your AP on DeB each round. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Perform Action \r\n	- \r\n	Var \r\n	 An