\r\n	-4 \r\n	-4 \r\n	+0 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n     1  Within each of these categories, apply only the highest absolute modifier.\r\n     2  Defender can only use passive DeC (not active). When applied to Ref, defender loses Dex and Int bonuses.\r\n     3  Same as  2 , but also treat the defenderโs Dex as 0 (-5 modifier).\r\n     4  Note that an entangled creature also suffers a Dex penalty that can further affect defenses.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Cover:  Includes low walls, battlements, wall corners, trees, opponents between you and the attacker, and other hard obstructions. Attacks of opportunity cannot be made against creatures that have cover against you. Cover provides a +4 bonus to Hide checks.\r\n     Good cover:  Includes arrow slits and peering around a corner or tree. You gain the equivalent of Greater Evasion (half or no damage from area attacks against Ref). You also gain a +10 bonus to Hide checks.\r\n     Total Cover:  Non-area attacks against creatures with total cover always fail. You gain Greater Evasion against area attacks.\r\n     Concealment:  Includes anything that makes the defender difficult to see properly, such as fog, shadows, foliage, curtains, etc.\r\n     Good concealment:  Includes dense fog, dense foliage, near-total darkness, etc. Attacks of opportunity cannot be made against creatures that have good concealment.\r\n     Total concealment:  The +10 DeC bonus assumes that the attacker is still able to target the right square. Attacks of opportunity cannot be made against creatures that have total concealment.\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    For creatures that occupy more than one square, special rules for cover and concealment apply.\r\n    When a creature larger than one square is attacking a defender, it can choose any of its squares to determine the defenderโs cover and concealment.\r\n    When a creature larger than one square is defending, all of its squares must have cover or concealment against the attacker in order to receive any bonuses.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Attacks of Opportunity \r\n     \r\n    Any creature that is able to make melee attacks with a primary attack form and is not flat-footed threatens all squares\r\n    between its minimum and maximum reach.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If an opponent in a threatened square performs any action that provokes attacks of opportunity,\r\n    the threatening creature can choose to make such an attack of opportunity for free.\r\n    The threatening creature cannot make attacks of opportunity against a creature that has cover or at least good concealment against it.\r\n    A creature can normally only make a single attack of opportunity per round, but certain skills and magical effects can grant additional ones.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    An attack of opportunity can be any melee attack action that requires 8 AP or less, but it does not actually cost the attacker any APs.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Attacks of opportunity interrupt the normal initiative sequence and are resolved before the action that provoked the attack.\r\n    This means that a successful attack of opportunity can prevent the triggering action from being completed.\r\n    For example, if an opponent\'s movement triggers an attack of opportunity, a successful trip attack can prevent that movement.\r\n    And if an attack of opportunity triggered by spellcasting causes damage, the damage caused will penalize the caster\'s spellcasting check.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Note that it is possible for an attack of opportunity to trigger its own attacks of opportunity.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Weapon Size and Attack Speed \r\n     \r\n    The size of a weapon is important in many ways, since it affects attack speed, reach, and how easily the weapon can be wielded.\r\n    Weapon size typically refers to the weapon\'s object size, but in some cases that size by itself is not the only important factor.\r\n    For example, when determining how a weapon is to be wielded,\r\n    the size of the weapon relative to its wielder, and also whether the weapon was made for a wielder of that size or not,\r\n    are more crucial factors than the weapon\'s absolute object size.\r\n    For this reason, it is important to understand the difference between weapon/object size,\r\n    wielder/creature size, and the weapon\'s made-for-size.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Let us use a longsword made for a Medium-sized wielder as an example.\r\n    Its weapon or object size is Small, and its made-for-size is Medium.\r\n    This means that a Medium-sized humanoid can wield it as a one-handed weapon without penalties.\r\n    A Small-sized humanoid can also wield it but would have to use two hands (and suffer some attack penalties).\r\n    A Large-sized humanoid can wield it as a \"light weapon\" (but would also suffer some attack penalties).\r\n    Likewise, a longsword made for a Large-sized wielder would be a Medium-sized object and could, for example,\r\n    be wielded by a Medium-sized humanoid using two hands (but with attack penalties).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For a creature\'s natural attacks, each attack form has its size specified as relative to the whole creature.\r\n    For example, a humanoid of Medium size typically has 2 arms that count as Diminutive weapons and 2 legs that count as Tiny weapons.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, the creature\'s own size is used as the weapon size for brawling attacks.\r\n     \r\n     Attack Speed \r\n     \r\n    A weapon\'s attack speed (i.e. the AP cost of a given attack) is determined first and foremost by the weapon\'s object size.\r\n    Simply apply the size-based attack speed modifier to the base AP cost of the attack you wish to perform.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For example, the base AP cost for a normal melee attack is 8 AP,\r\n    and this is also the actual cost for a melee attack with a Medium-sized weapon.\r\n    To use a Medium-sized humanoid for further examples, its actual attack speed can vary from\r\n    5 AP for a hand attack (a Diminutive-sized weapon with -3 attack speed modifier) to\r\n    8 AP for a two-handed weapon such as a halberd (a Medium-sized weapon with a +0 attack speed modifier).\r\n    A Large-sized humanoid could make similar attacks, its actual attack speed varying from\r\n    6 AP for a hand attack (a Tiny-sized weapon with -2 attack speed modifier) to\r\n    9 AP for a two-handed weapon made for a Large creature (a Large-sized weapon with a +1 attack speed modifier).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Attack speed can be further modified by certain skills and magical effects.\r\n     \r\n     How to Wield \r\n     \r\n    The object size of a weapon relative to the size of the wielder determines how easily it can be wielded.\r\n    Every weapon can be categorized as follows based on the size difference:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Light: Object size is two steps smaller than wielder size.\r\n        It can be used effectively for multi-attacks and also in cramped situations (such as while grappling).\r\n        Light projectile weapons can be fired (but not loaded) with one hand. \r\n         One-handed: Object size is one step smaller than the wielder size.\r\n        It can be easily wielded in one hand, but it can also be wielded as a two-handed weapon (for a +2 Str bonus to damage).\r\n        One-handed projectile weapons can be fired (but not loaded) with one hand (but with a -2 attack penalty). \r\n         Two-handed: Object size is the same as the wielder size.\r\n        It has to be wielded in two hands (giving a +2 Str bonus to damage). \r\n         Too small: An object three or more sizes smaller than the creature cannot be effectively wielded as a weapon. \r\n         Too large: An object larger than the creature cannot be effectively wielded as a weapon. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Note that natural attacks always count as light weapons, regardless of their relative size.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When used for a multi-attack, double weapons count as one one-handed and one light weapon.\r\n    They can only be effectively used in this way by wielders that match the weapon\'s made-for-size.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When the weapon\'s made-for-size differs from the wielder size, all attack rolls suffer a -2 circumstance penalty per step of difference.\r\n    For example, a longsword made for a Large creature is a Medium-sized object that can be wielded two-handed by a Medium-sized humanoid (but with a -2 attack penalty).\r\n    Similarly, a two-handed sword made for a Small creature can act as a one-handed weapon for a Medium-sized creature (-2 attack penalty),\r\n    and it can act as a light weapon for a Large-sized creature (-4 attack penalty).\r\n     \r\n     Weapon Reach \r\n     \r\n    As the old saying goes, don\'t bring a dagger to a swordfight.\r\n    Attacking someone who has a bigger weapon than you can be a dangerous prospect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    First of all, a weapon\'s minimum and maximum reach is measured in squares.\r\n    The weapon can potentially threaten or be used against any opponent that is located within this range,\r\n    making it either dangerous or time-consuming for an opponent to perform any action that provokes attacks of opportunity.\r\n    A weapon with a reach of 0-1, for example, can be used against targets in your own square and up to one square away.\r\n    A reach of 2-2 means that the weapon threatens all squares that are two squares away,\r\n    but creatures in squares adjacent to you are safe from attack.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Furthermore, whenever a melee attack is made,\r\n    compare the object size of the attacking weapon with the object size of each primary attack form or weapon of the defender.\r\n    If the defender has one or more threatening weapons larger than the attacking weapon,\r\n    the attack provokes an attack of opportunity from the defender.\r\n    For multi-attacks you count the size of the largest weapon used against each defender.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    However, there are ways to make melee attacks with small weapons without provoking attacks of opportunity.\r\n    One common way is to make a charge attack instead of just a regular melee attack.\r\n    Another way is to use a Feint action to trick your opponent and bypass his defenses.\r\n    Furthermore, some conditions (such as flat-footed or stunned) will typically render a defender unable to make attacks of opportunity.\r\n    Also remember that a defender is limited in the number of opportunity attacks it can make each round,\r\n    and that it is unable to make opportunity attacks against any attacker that has cover or good concealment.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Improvised and Untrained Weapons \r\n     \r\n    Whenever an attacker uses a weapon that it has no skill with, the following penalties apply.\r\n    The same penalties apply for using a non-weapon item as a weapon, such as clubbing someone with a chair or simply throwing a rock at someone.\r\n    The same penalties also apply for using a weapon in a way it was not meant to work, such as throwing a melee weapon not balanced for throwing,\r\n    using a throwing weapon or projectile weapon in melee, changing the weapon\'s damage from HP to SP or vice versa.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         -4 penalty on all attack rolls. \r\n         The weapon gets a threat range of 20 and crit multiplier of ร2. \r\n         The weapon\'s or item\'s parry bonus is halved. \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Mounted Combat \r\n     \r\n    Mounts that are trained for war (or mounts that are natural predators) will automatically move\r\n    as directed by their rider, even in the heat of combat.\r\n    However, you still need to make Ride checks if you want to guide the mount only with your knees\r\n    (freeing up your hands for weapon-wielding and spell-casting).\r\n    You also need to make Ride checks to direct your mount to attack opponents.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A mount that has not been trained for combat will need Ride checks for all movement as well as attacks.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The following special rules apply to mounted combat:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         The mount uses its own AP and MP for action point bonuses and actions. One exception is that brawling attacks with a mount cost AP both for you and the mount. You cannot use your own MP while mounted, but you can convert AP to MP for the dismount action. You can spend AP on other actions while your mount performs full-round movement actions (jog, run, and sprint). \r\n         Your mount acts on your initiative. You can mix your own actions with those of your mount. For example, you can start by spending the mount\'s MP on movement, then spend your own AP to make an attack, spend additional MP on another move, and then let the mount spend its AP on an attack. \r\n         When charging with a mount, both you and the mount enjoy the charging bonuses as well as suffer the penalties. \r\n         It is harder to wield a two-handed or double weapon from a mount, giving you a -2 attack penalty. \r\n         Many brawling attacks, such as bull rush and overrun, can be performed with a mount. Use the best AB, ability, skill, and size modifiers, your or the mountโs, for these attacks. \r\n         The mountโs spacing is used for both the mount and the rider. \r\n         Attacks of opportunity provoked by movement can target either the mount or rider. \r\n         When attacking a creature smaller than your mount, you receive the โhigher groundโ attack bonuses. \r\n         An attack that succeeds in forcibly moving you will automatically knock you off your mount. \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Attack Types and Damage \r\n     \r\n    Skills, actions, and spells will sometimes refer to different types of attacks and weapons.\r\n    This categorization can be rather confusing, especially since many of the categories overlap.\r\n    The most common attack and weapon types are listed here, together with their associated skill abbreviations:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n          Attack:  Includes every type of attack, including natural weapon attacks, manufactured weapon attacks, and supernatural attacks. \r\n         \r\n              Weapon:  Includes all weapon types, natural as well as manufactured (but not supernatural attacks). \r\n	         \r\n	              Melee weapons (WpMel):  Close combat weapons, including most natural weapons. Also includes thrown weapons, even those that cannot easily be used in melee combat. \r\n	              Natural weapons (WpNat):  Includes hands, feet, claws, bite attacks, tailsweeps, etc. They count as melee weapons, unless otherwise specified. \r\n	              Manufactured weapons:  Includes all non-natural weapons, such as axes, swords, bows, shields, etc. Each type has its own skill. \r\n		         \r\n		              Projectile weapons (WpPrj):  Includes all hand-held, ranged weapons that require ammunition. \r\n		              Exotic weapons (WpExo):  Special category including weapons that require special training. \r\n		              Siege weapons (WpSie):  Includes all weapons large enough to be used by more than one person. \r\n		              Shields (WpShd):  Shields count as weapons, although they are made more for parrying than attacking. \r\n		         \r\n	              Monk weapons (WpMnk):  Special category covering those weapons often used by martial artists. \r\n	         \r\n              Brawling attacks (WpBrl):  Includes attacks made with the whole body, such as grappling and tackling. \r\n              Supernatural attacks:  Includes ray attacks (WpRay), area attacks (WpAre), and body &amp; mind attacks (WpBaM).\r\n            Natural weapons are not considered supernatural, even when they are used to deliver supernatural effects. \r\n	          Ranged attacks:  Includes thrown melee weapons, projectile weapons, some rare natural weapons, and many supernatural attacks. \r\n	          Generic weapons (WpGen):  Includes most non-exotic weapons, including natural weapons, brawling, and even ray attacks. \r\n         \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Weapon Damage \r\n     \r\n    Total Weapon Damage = Base Weapon Damage + Str mod + DaB\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Weapons cause damage to the targetโs HP or SP, according to the base damage listed for the creature or in the equipment chapter.\r\n    The attacker can choose to change the weaponโs damage (from SP to HP and vice versa), but this typically incurs a -4 attack penalty.\r\n    Changing damage from HP to SP also turns the damage type into B (blunt damage).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Strength modifier: An attackerโs strength modifies the damage of most melee, thrown, and some projectile weapons\r\n    (as specified in the equipment chapter). When a weapon is wielded in two hands, increase the Str modifier by +2.\r\n    A strength modifier can never improve the damage of a weapon by more than its maximum base damage dice.\r\n    For example, a dagger with a base damage of d4 can never enjoy a higher Str modifier than +4.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Minimum damage: Modifiers can reduce the damage caused by a weapon but never below 1 HP/SP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Exceptional hits: When a weapon attack results in an exceptional success or better, damage resistance is halved.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Critical hits: When a weapon attack results in a critical success, the damage is multiplied by the factor specified for the weapon.\r\n    If no other multiplier is specified, use ร2. All damage is multiplied, whether it consists of HP, SP, PP, or ability damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Multiplying damage: Some effects (a critical hit, for example) will multiply the damage of a weapon.\r\n    The same multiplicative factor applies to all normal modifiers (including AP-based DaB), but not to extra damage dice.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Hot or burning weapons: A weapon that is on fire or glowing hot deals an additional d2 to d4 HP of fire damage.\r\n     \r\n     Supernatural Touch Damage \r\n     \r\n    The damage from a touch attack depends on the type of attack and varies widely.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Exceptional hits: When a touch attack results in an exceptional success or better, resistance (if any) is halved.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Critical hits: When a touch attack results in a critical success, the damage or effect is often doubled.\r\n    All damage is multiplied, whether it consists of HP, SP, PP, or ability damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Multiplying damage: Some effects (a critical hit, for example) can multiply the damage of a touch.\r\n    The same multiplicative factor applies to all normal modifiers, but not to extra damage dice.\r\n     \r\n     Supernatural Weapon Damage \r\n     \r\n    When a supernatural effect is delivered through a melee weapon, calculate weapon damage as normal and then apply the additional effect(s).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Exceptional and critical hits will have normal effect on both the weapon damage and the supernatural effect.\r\n     \r\n     Ray Damage \r\n     \r\n    The damage from a ray attack depends on the type of attack and varies widely.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Exceptional hits: When a ray attack results in an exceptional success or better, resistance (if any) is halved.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Critical hits: When a ray attack results in a critical success, the damage or effect is often doubled.\r\n    All damage is multiplied, whether it consists of HP, SP, PP, or ability damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Multiplying damage: Some effects (a critical hit, for example) can multiply the damage of a ray.\r\n    The same multiplicative factor applies to all normal modifiers, but not to extra damage dice.\r\n     \r\n     Area Effect Damage \r\n     \r\n    Area attacks are typically made against the Reflex defense of potential victims.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A critical success often inflicts extra damage and also has a chance to destroy the victimโs exposed equipment.\r\n    Roll 1d4 and randomly select that number of exposed items (those not protected by the victimโs armor).\r\n    Apply the full energy damage to those items, but note that most objects have energy resistance,\r\n    take reduced damage from many energy types, and are immune to radiant and necrotic damage.\r\n     \r\n     Fortitude and Will Attack Damage \r\n     \r\n    A critical success will often inflict extra damage or cause additional effects.\r\n     \r\n    \r\n    Damage Types \r\n     \r\n    The different damage types can be categorized as follows:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Physical Damage \r\n         \r\n             Blunt Damage \r\n             Piercing Damage \r\n             Slashing Damage \r\n         \r\n         Energy Damage \r\n         \r\n             Acid Damage \r\n             Cold Damage \r\n             Electricity/Lightning Damage \r\n             Fire/Heat Damage \r\n             Necrotic Damage \r\n             Radiant Damage \r\n             Sonic Damage \r\n         \r\n         Physical Fatigue Damage \r\n         Mental Fatigue Damage \r\n         Ability Damage \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Physical Damage \r\n     \r\n     Blunt  damage causes a loss in HP and/or SP.\r\n    An attack that causes 50% or more of a creature\'s HP or SP in blunt damage requires an Acrobatics (Maintain Balance) check\r\n    against a DC equal to the damage. Failure means that the creature is knocked prone; for every 5 levels of failure, the creature is also\r\n    knocked back one square.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most [Force] effects cause blunt damage.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Piercing  damage causes a loss in HP.\r\n    Objects and creatures that have resistance to critical hits of +10 or better take only half damage from piercing attacks (after reduction for DR).\r\n    The reason is that piercing damage is based largely on striking sensitive areas.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Slashing  damage causes a loss in HP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Damage resistance (DR) reduces every instance of physical damage.\r\n     \r\n    Energy Damage \r\n     \r\n     Acid  damage causes a loss in HP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Moderate  cold  causes a loss of SP. Severe cold causes a loss of HP and/or SP.\r\n    Also note that extreme cold can instantaneously freeze water (and many other liquids) in its area of effect, potentially trapping creatures within.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Electricity  and lightning usually causes a loss of both HP and SP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Moderate  heat  causes a loss of SP. Severe heat and fire causes a loss of HP and/or SP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Necrotic  damage (also known as negative energy or death energy) causes a loss in HP and/or SP when affecting living creatures.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Radiant  damage (also known as positive energy or life energy) causes a loss in HP when affecting living creatures.\r\n    However, moderate amounts of radiance used with care can be used to heal injuries and even restore life.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Sonic  damage causes a loss of HP and/or SP.\r\n    An attack that causes 50% or more of a creature\'s HP or SP in sonic damage requires an Acrobatics (Maintain Balance) check\r\n    against a DC equal to the damage. Failure means that the creature is knocked prone; for every 5 levels of failure, the creature is also\r\n    knocked back one square.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Energy resistance of the appropriate type reduces energy damage.\r\n    Note, however, that the amount of resistance is the maximum reduction per round (not per instance).\r\n     \r\n     Physical Fatigue Damage \r\n     \r\n    Attacks and effects that cause  physical fatigue damage  result in a decrease in SP. Serious physical fatigue can cause ability damage to Con.\r\n     \r\n     Mental Fatigue Damage \r\n     \r\n    Attacks and effects that cause  mental fatigue damage  result in a decrease in PP. Serious mental fatigue can cause ability damage to Wis.\r\n     \r\n     Ability Damage \r\n     \r\n     Ability damage  causes a temporary reduction of the specified ability score(s).\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Morale \r\n     \r\n    Some situations call for a morale check to determine whether a creature keeps fighting or\r\n    runs away, whether a captive succumbs to intimidation or laughs in the captor\'s face,\r\n    whether an army continues to fight effectively or is routed, etc.\r\n    A morale check is basically an attack against the creature\'s Will defense, with a number of situational modifiers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A morale check is effectively a [Fear] effect.\r\n    Creatures resistant or immune to [Fear] enjoy the same bonuses against morale checks.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Morale checks should be used primarily against NPCs and monsters.\r\n    Player characters should only suffer morale checks when exposed to particularly terrifying monsters, [Fear] magic, or other extreme situations.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Morale Check Modifiers \r\n     \r\n     Situation \r\n     Circumstance Modifier \r\n   	  \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Injury \r\n	 +2 for injured, +4 for bloodied, +8 for near death \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Physical Fatigue \r\n	 +2 for fatigued, +4 for exhausted \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Mental Fatigue \r\n	 +2 for tired, +4 for drained \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Loss of Allies \r\n	 +1 per 10% of perceived losses \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Loss of Enemies \r\n	 -1 per 10% of perceived losses \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Leadership \r\n	 Varies \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Inferior Enemy \r\n	 -1 to -10 (DM discretion) \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Superior Enemy \r\n	 +1 to +10 (DM discretion) \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Morale Check Results \r\n     \r\n     Check vs Will \r\n     Result \r\n   	  \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Success \r\n	 Creature becomes shaken \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Outstanding Success \r\n	 Creature becomes frightened \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Exceptional Success \r\n	 Creature becomes panicked \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Critical Success \r\n	 Creature cowers in fear \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Failure \r\n	 Creature can act normally \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n		     \r\n         \r\n\r\n		\r\n         \r\n        \r\n            \r\n          \r\n		\r\n     \r\n \r\n ','2013-01-26',50.86,'8d31d737bd18cf0c9598c5d8e5f7b75d',0,2),(76,2,'http://localhost/rold20/hb05_magic.php','RoL d20 - Rules of Magic','','\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n	\r\n\r\n		\r\n	            \r\n	             \r\n	            \r\n	                 \r\n	                    RoL d20 Role-Playing System\r\n	                 \r\n	             \r\n			  \r\n		\r\n        \r\n			\r\n		 Handbook \r\n         \r\n             Introduction  \r\n             Core Mechanics  \r\n             \r\n                 Characteristics  \r\n                 Action Checks  \r\n                 Modifiers  \r\n                 Descriptors  \r\n                 Prerequisites  \r\n                 Conditions  \r\n                 Special Senses  \r\n                 Special Abilities  \r\n             \r\n             Character Generation  \r\n             \r\n                 Ability Scores  \r\n                 Character Races  \r\n                 Character Classes  \r\n                 Other Characteristics  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Combat  \r\n             \r\n                 Combat Sequence  \r\n                 Action Points  \r\n                 Combat Modifiers  \r\n                 Attack Types  \r\n                 Damage Types  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Magic  \r\n             \r\n                 Casting Spells  \r\n                 Learning Spells  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Environment  \r\n             \r\n                 Movement  \r\n                 Environment  \r\n                 The Multiverse  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Culture  \r\n             Rules of Engagement  \r\n             \r\n                 Encounters  \r\n                 Experience  \r\n                 Treasure  \r\n             \r\n             List of Skills  \r\n             \r\n                 Skill Availability  \r\n                 Skill Descriptions  \r\n             \r\n             List of Actions  \r\n             List of Spells  \r\n             List of Equipment  \r\n             \r\n	             Mundane Items  \r\n	             Complex Items  \r\n	             Item Modifications  \r\n	             Materials  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Creatures  \r\n             \r\n	             Aberrations  \r\n	             Animals  \r\n	             Monstrous Animals  \r\n	             Constructs  \r\n	             Dragons  \r\n	             Elementals  \r\n	             Humanoids  \r\n	             Monstrous Humanoids  \r\n	             Outsiders  \r\n	             Plants &amp; Fungi  \r\n	             Undead  \r\n	             Templates  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Cultures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Rules of Magic \r\n     \r\n    Magic plays a vital part in D&amp;D and encompasses a wide range of effects.\r\n    A fireball cast by a wizard, the healing done by a cleric, a druid changing into a wolf, a dragonโs fiery breath,\r\n    and an illithidโs mind blast are all different examples of magic.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Types and Sources of Magic \r\n     \r\n    Magic is the ability to manipulate reality in ways contrary to the laws of physics.\r\n    This requires a certain amount of skill as well as a source of energy.\r\n    The main difference between different caster types and different supernatural skills is where the energy is drawn from.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Arcane casters summon magical energy from other dimensions and planes of existence.\r\n    The most common sources are the positive and negative material planes, with the other elemental planes as a close second.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Divine casters summon magical energy from powerful outsiders and the spiritual planes.\r\n    This applies most of all to clerics and templars.\r\n    Druids and rangers, on the other hand, draw most of their spiritual energy from nature and its animals and plants.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Psionic users summon magical energy mostly from their inner selves and their own souls.\r\n    More proficient users can also learn to draw power from the Ethereal and Astral planes.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Different magic skills and sources of energy are more or less suited to different purposes.\r\n    A druid, for example, is attuned to and very good at manipulating plants, animals, and weather,\r\n    but he is not particularly good at affecting human minds or manipulating metal objects.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Casting Spells and Using Supernatural Powers \r\n     Spellcasting Procedure \r\n     \r\n    When you cast a spell, manifest a psionic power, or use some other supernatural power, follow these steps:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Select the spell or power. \r\n         Choose options and parameters (implements, activation time, range, duration, targets).\r\n        Also choose whether you want to boost the spell with additional PP or not. \r\n	         \r\n	         Calculate the total and actual PP costs (see below). \r\n	         Verify that you have sufficient skill level in all of the mandatory skills of the spell or power. \r\n	         \r\n         Start the casting. \r\n         At the end of the activation time, make an activation check. \r\n	          If the spell or power has multiple mandatory skills, use your highest skill level for the check.  \r\n         Deduct activation costs (in PP, XP, etc). \r\n         If activation is successful, choose exact area/targets and roll attack rolls (if any). \r\n         Determine and apply effects. \r\n     \r\n     Power Point Cost \r\n     \r\n    Casting spells and using most supernatural powers can be quite tiresome, even exhausting,\r\n    but the fatigue it causes is mental rather than physical. This is measured as a temporary loss of PP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The amount of PP that can be spent on a single spell or use of a power is limited by the userโs skill, one PP per level of skill.\r\n    If the spell or power has multiple mandatory skills, your lowest skill level sets the PP limit.\r\n    For inherent powers that are not connected to a skill, use the creatureโs RL instead.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Many spellcasting classes have access to\r\n    spell affinity skills  \r\n    that let you use an ability modifier to reduce the number of PP actually spent on activating a spell or power.\r\n    However, the maximum PP cost due to skill level is unaffected by this cost reduction.\r\n    If the spell or power has multiple mandatory skills, you only need spell affinity in one of them to be eligible for the PP cost reduction.\r\n    If you have multiple spell affinity skills that apply to the same spell, the cost reductions do not stack (use only the highest one).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A spellcaster or power user can boost or dampen a power by pouring more PP into it.\r\n    The maximum amount of PP that can be used to boost or dampen a power is equal to the userโs skill level (or RL, if no skill is applicable).\r\n    Boosting a power increases its PL, and dampening reduces its PL (for most purposes other than magic item cost calculation).\r\n    This boost or dampening affects the chance of overcoming magic resistance, anti-magic, and similar hindrances.\r\n    It also affects the difficulty of detecting, dispelling, counterspelling, etc. the power.\r\n    A spellcaster or power user cannot both boost and dampen the same power.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Base PP cost:  The PP cost of a spell or power without any parameter modifiers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Total PP cost:  The PP cost of a spell or power with all options and parameter modifiers added.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     PP boost:  Additional PP cost used to boost or dampen the spell or power.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Actual PP cost:  (Total cost) + (PP boost) โ (modification for spell affinities). Minimum 1 PP.\r\n     \r\n     Activation Check \r\n     \r\n    Casting a spell or using a supernatural power requires a d20 check,\r\n    referred to either as a supernatural activation check or a spellcasting check.\r\n    Although this check is mandatory, please remember that supernatural affinity allows the caster to \"take 10\" in most situations.\r\n    In the case of an attack power, simply activating the power is usually not enough;\r\n    one or more attack rolls are then required in order for the power to successfully affect the intended targets.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    There are a number of situations where a supernatural action can be resisted or otherwise made more difficult to perform,\r\n    as shown below.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n     Supernatural activation check:  d20 + Arcane/Divine/Psi skill + (Affinity skill ability mod) + (PP boost) + MAM vs. DC 10 + (total PP cost)\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Note that when boosting a power, \"PP boost\" is a bonus, but when dampening a power, \"PP boost\" is a penalty.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Counterspelling \r\n         Replace base DC 10 with (opposing spellcasting check) \r\n         Already active spell or power \r\n         Powerโs PL vs. 0 \r\n         Undead or construct \r\n         Creatureโs TL vs. 0 \r\n         Summoned creature \r\n         Summoning powerโs PL vs. 0 \r\n         Supernatural item \r\n         Itemโs PL vs. 0 \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Add the following modifiers to the difficulty:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Against active opposing power \r\n         + opposing powerโs PL \r\n         Antimagic zone \r\n         + AM (level of antimagic) \r\n         Wild magic zone \r\n         + WM (level of wild magic) \r\n         Magic resistance \r\n         + MR (this modifier applies only to the target or targets with MR) \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For inherent abilities and other situations where no skill level is applicable, use the creatureโs RL instead.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Note that when casting spells for which you have no affinity skill, no ability modifier is applied to the spellcasting check.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If you are wearing armor you are not proficient with, EP should be applied to supernatural activation checks as well as supernatural attack rolls.\r\n     \r\n     Supernatural Activation vs. Magic Resistance \r\n     \r\n    When you try to use a supernatural action check against a creature or object that has \r\n    magic resistance  (MR), \r\n    the MR is added to the difficulty. If the check fails due to the added MR,\r\n    then the action has reduced or no effect against the target with the resistance, but it affects other creatures normally.\r\n    Note that only one activation check is made, and that check is compared against the MR of each potential target.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When a creature or object with MR is subjected to an active supernatural effect, compare the MR against the effectโs power level.\r\n    If the MR is higher, the effect fails to affect the target with resistance.\r\n     \r\n     Supernatural Activation in Anti-Magic Zone \r\n     \r\n    If you try to use a supernatural action in an area that has anti-magic, the anti-magic level (AM) is added to the difficulty.\r\n    If the check fails due to the added AM, the action will have reduced or no effect.\r\n    If you are within the AM area, the entire action is affected. If you are outside the area but the effect is wholly or partially in the AM area,\r\n    then any part of the effect that is within the AM area suffers the reduced effect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When an active supernatural effect, magical device, or conjured creature enters an area with AM,\r\n    compare the AM against the effectโs, deviceโs, or creatureโs power level.\r\n    If the AM is higher, the effect is temporarily dispelled, the device is temporarily rendered inactive, and the creature is unable to enter the area.\r\n     \r\n     Supernatural Activation in Wild Magic Zone \r\n     \r\n    If you try to use a supernatural action in an area that has wild magic, the wild magic level (WM) is added to the difficulty.\r\n    If the check fails due to the added WM, then the action suffers a wild effect.\r\n    This can happen either if you are standing in the WM area or if the actionโs effect is wholly or partially in the WM area.\r\n     \r\n     Activation Check Results \r\n     \r\n    Regardless of the result of a spellcasting check, the cost in time and PP has to be paid in full by the caster.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    As mentioned before, an activated spell or supernatural effect gets a PL equal to (total PP cost + PP boost).\r\n    If this is not applicable, use the skill level or creatureโs RL instead.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Spellcasting Results in Normal or Antimagic Zones \r\n     \r\n     Check Result \r\n     Effect \r\n   	  \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Success \r\n	 Spell or power works as intended. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Failure \r\n	 Spell has negligible effect (one tenth damage, -20 attack roll, reduced area, etc.) \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Outstanding Failure \r\n	 Spell or power fizzles in a shower of sparks. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Exceptional Failure \r\n	 Spell or power fizzles with no noticeable effect whatsoever. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n    \r\n\r\n	\r\n   	Spellcasting Results in Wild Magic Zones \r\n     \r\n     Check Result \r\n     Effect \r\n   	  \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Critical Success \r\n	 Spell or power has increased effect (double damage, increased area, longer duration, etc.) \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Outstanding Success \r\n	 Spell or power works as intended and costs no PP. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Success \r\n	 Spell or power works as intended. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Failure \r\n	 Spell has negligible effect (one tenth damage, -20 attack roll, reduced area, etc.) \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Outstanding Failure \r\n	 Instead of the spellโs effect, innocuous item or items related to the effect appear in the target area.\r\n	Or caster or user suffers bizarre side effect related to the spellโs normal effect. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Exceptional Failure \r\n	 Effect fails and surge of magical energy (random type) deals 2 HP per PL to the caster or user. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Critical Failure \r\n	 Spell takes effect against the caster or an ally instead of intended target.\r\n	Or spell produces some sort of contrary or opposite effect (cold instead of fire, for example). \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     Maintaining a Spell or Power \r\n     \r\n    Some spells require continuous concentration to maintain. While concentrating, you can only use half your AP and MP for other actions,\r\n    and those actions must not themselves require concentration. Anything that can break your concentration requires an appropriate skill check.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Learning Spells and Powers \r\n     \r\n    Skill levels in the various spell skills determine how many spells a creature can learn.\r\n    A certain number of spells or new options can be learned automatically whenever a skill level is gained.\r\n    Each option for a spell is learned separately, and when a new spell is learned, you learn none of its options for free.\r\n    The spells or options learned must have the appropriate skill as a mandatory skill,\r\n    and you must have sufficient skill levels in all of the mandatory skills.\r\n     \r\n    \r\n	\r\n		\r\n   	Spell Learning \r\n     \r\n     Skill Type \r\n     Automatic Spell Learning \r\n     Maximum Spell Learning \r\n   	  \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Arcane - ... \r\n	 One new spell or option every skill level \r\n	 Two spells/options per skill level \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Divine - ... \r\n	 Two new spells or options every skill level \r\n	 Unlimited \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Psi - ... \r\n	 One new spell or option every two skill levels (but starting at 1st) \r\n	 One spell/option per skill level \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Wizard Affinity - Generalist \r\n	 Two new spells or options every skill level (belonging to any Arcane skill) \r\n	 - \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Spells, powers, and options that are not automatically learned can be acquired with the \"Learn Spell\" action.\r\n    Note that for spells that you gain access to through special skills (such as Bardic Music or Wild Shape),\r\n    the \"Learn Spell\" action is always required.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Access to spells is rarely a big problem, since most temples, guilds, and masters are willing to teach their apprentices new spells\r\n    in exchange for services rendered or a modest amount of money.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Arcane, Divine, and Psionic Writings \r\n     \r\n    With these new rules, there are no longer any spellcasters that need to memorize their spells from spellbooks.\r\n    Nevertheless, many spellcasters still collect or create writings that describe how to cast their spells.\r\n    Some such writings are created as a source of income, others as instruction books for apprentices,\r\n    some as religious texts, and still others as research notes.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most writings are books and tomes of some sort, but more exotic variants also exist.\r\n    For example, a sorcerer may choose to write down spells on dragonhide, a church may keep their most important religious writings on sheets of silver,\r\n    and some psionicists may use crystals to store their teachings. In other words, the type, size, and weight of such writings can vary greatly.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Barring such unusual storage devices, there is a default size and cost for writing that describes a spell or power.\r\n    First, calculate the maximum PP cost of the spell โ add all options and the maximum cost of each parameter.\r\n    If the sum exceeds 30, use 30 instead as the upper limit. The writing takes up one page per maximum PP cost,\r\n    and each page requires 20 sp and 2 h to write. A typical spellbook contains up to 300 pages.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Researching Spells and Powers \r\n     \r\n    The spells and powers listed in these rules are only the ones most commonly taught to spell casters and psionicists.\r\n    It is possible, however, for such practitioners to research and develop new powers based on the skills they know.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Spell Modifiers \r\n     \r\n    The parameters for spells are the same as for any other action, except as described below.\r\n     \r\n     Implements \r\n     \r\n    Verbal (V): You speak mystical words in a firm voice. If you are unable to speak, you cannot cast spells with a V component.\r\n    If you are deafened, a spellcasting check with a -4 penalty is required.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Somatic (S): You make mystical gestures with at least one hand. The hand must either be empty or holding an appropriate implement, and the arm must be relatively free to move.\r\n    Whether an implement is appropriate or not depends on the type of skill you are using - wands are suitable for arcane skills, holy symbols for divine skills, etc.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Material (M) or Focus (F): You use a material component or special focus to aid in the casting.\r\n    The material or focus must be held in or touched by the casterโs hand during the casting,\r\n    but the retrieval of an easily accessible material is included in the spellโs activation time.\r\n    A material is consumed by the casting, while a focus is not.\r\n     \r\n     Range \r\n     \r\n    Most spells with a range of touch and a single target will let the caster hold the charge and make new attacks indefinitely,\r\n    but the first successful touch always discharges the spell. If the caster casts a new spell, the held charge dissipates without effect.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Residuum \r\n     \r\n    Residuum is a liquid form of raw magic and life energy.\r\n    It can be used in place of XP when creating magic items and casting spells that cost XP.\r\n    Residuum is typically produced by using the Enchant Item skill to disenchant a magic item.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Residuum is a silvery liquid similar to quicksilver in appearance, but it has a slightly luminescent quality.\r\n    Amounts of residuum are measured in XP, its volume is 1 dl per 1000 XP, and it has a density of 10 kg per l.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Residuum is usually stored in glass vials and flasks.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If anyone is crazy enough to drink residuum (or is forced to do so), apply the effects of a random spell to the drinker.\r\n    The maximum PL of that effect is 1 per 200 XP of residuum.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Magic Items \r\n     \r\n    Magic items are usually similar to mundane items, except that they have been infused with and enhanced by magic.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Item Appearance \r\n     \r\n    A majority of magic items differ little in appearance from their mundane versions,\r\n    but they are often exceptionally well made or decorated with gems and precious metals.\r\n    Some may even be obviously magical, glowing or sparkling with discharges of arcane energy.\r\n    Others, however, may be โdisguisedโ as common or even cheap items.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Many magic items are of masterwork, outstanding, or exceptional workmanship in addition to being magical.\r\n    Not only does this make the item more valuable, but it also makes the item more useful in situations where its magic fails for whatever reason.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Identifying Magic Items \r\n     \r\n    The Spellcraft and Enchant Item skills can be used to do some basic identification of a magic item.\r\n    Successful checks can identify potions and reveal the type and level of power involved.\r\n    They can also be used to attune oneself to supernatural implements and power sources.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    For more detailed identification, spells such as Detect Magic and Analyze Dweomer are required.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Using Magic Items \r\n     \r\n    Many magic items need only be worn or used normally to provide their benefits to the owner.\r\n    For example, a suit of magic armor protects its wearer automatically, a Ring of Regeneration starts working as soon as it is put on oneโs finger,\r\n    a magic sword gives bonuses to attack and damage when it is wielded, etc. Such items usually require no special skills or powers to wear or use.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Other items must be activated in some way, possibly requiring a spoken phrase, a special gesture,\r\n    or just a mental command.\r\n    Some items, such as wands and spell scrolls, even require specific skills and action checks to use properly.\r\n    See the \r\n    list of actions  \r\n    for special actions related to the use of magic items.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Creating Magic Items \r\n     \r\n    In order to create a magic item, a number of requirements must be fulfilled.\r\n    Multiple individuals can cooperate in providing these requirements.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         The enchanters must first procure the mundane item that is to be enchanted. \r\n         Decide which powers to add to the item (see the list of magical item modifications). \r\n	     \r\n	         Start with the PL of the most expensive power. \r\n	         For each additional power that can be said to follow the same \"theme\", add 0.5 times the power\'s PL. \r\n	         For the remaining non-\"theme\" powers, add each power\'s full PL. \r\n	         For any power added to an item of the inappropriate type, multiply its PL addition by 1.5. \r\n	         The end result is the item\'s minimum PL. \r\n	     \r\n         Choose the item\'s actual PL (no lower than the minimum PL calculated above). \r\n         Use the itemโs minimum and actual PL to determine the itemโs base price\r\n        (see below for each item type and also for special price modifications). \r\n         The main enchanter has to have an Enchant Item skill level equal to or higher than the itemโs actual PL. \r\n         For each power, at least one enchanter must know the appropriate spell(s) and/or Enchant Item specialization(s) at a level matching the PL of that power. \r\n         The enchanters must provide the raw materials (equivalent to half of the base price). \r\n         The main enchanter must infuse the item with a portion of his life force (XP equal to 40% of the base price in gp).\r\n        Residuum can be used to replace all or some of this cost. \r\n         When upgrading an already enchanted item to something more powerful, calculate PL and base price as normal.\r\n        The material cost, XP cost, and the time required is based on the price difference between the original and finished item. \r\n         When altering an already enchanted item to something different, or when transferring powers from one item to another,\r\n        treat the alteration or transfer as two separate actions,\r\n        one to extract residuum for removed powers, and another to enchant with new powers. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A damaged magic item can be repaired with regular Crafting skills.\r\n    The magic of an item is not lost until it is completely destroyed, so no supernatural skill is needed for mere repairs.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The following modifications can be applied to most item types for free:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Skill-restricted item: Using the item\'s powers and enhancements requires a minimum skill level \r\n         Race/class-restricted item: The item\'s powers and enhancements can only be used by a specific race or class \r\n         Level-restricted item: The item\'s user can only enjoy powers and enhancements of a PL equal to or lower than his own TL.\r\n        Note that this can provide gradual access to powers that have a variable PL cost. \r\n         Bonded item: Item\'s powers and enhancements can only be used by someone who has successfully completed an attunement ritual (as specified by the item\'s creator) \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Potions and Oils \r\n     \r\n    Potions and oils are basically spells concocted and distilled into a liquid form.\r\n    Potions take effect when you drink them, while oils take effect when they are applied to the skin of a creature (or the surface an object).\r\n    Certain oils can even be activated by throwing and breaking the container against the target (treat this as a splash attack).\r\n    Such oils are often stored in breakable glass beads rather than vials,\r\n    and their size make them suitable as ammunition for small-, medium-, or large-sized slings.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Potions and oils usually come in small vials containing a single dose.\r\n    A typical dose is 2 to 3 cl, and vials are usually around 3 cm wide and 5 cm high.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A potion can be based on any arcane or divine spell with the restrictions listed below.\r\n    All other options and specifics are determined by the brewer of the potion or oil, not by the one who uses it.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    	 Action Time must be 9 AP or less \r\n    	 If implements include M, the material must be included in the brewing \r\n    	 Implements must not include F \r\n    	 Range must be Personal, Touch, or 0 \r\n    	 Target must be You or 1 creature for potions (oils can also have 1 object or an area as target) \r\n    	 Maximum total PP cost is 5 \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Minimum PL = Spell\'s total PP cost (without PP cost reductions for supernatural affinities)\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 5 + material cost\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Psionic Tattoos \r\n     \r\n    Psionic tattoos are psionic powers stored in the form of a colorful geometric design on a creature\'s body.\r\n    A tattoo can be activated by the wearer (and only the wearer) by touching it and concentrating for a few seconds.\r\n    When activated, the tattoo\'s power takes effect, and the tattoo itself immediately fades away.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Tattoos usually cover an area no larger than 10 by 10 cm, but there is no actual limit other than the size of the creature\'s skin.\r\n    A single creature is limited to a maximum of twenty tattoos - adding another one will create an interference\r\n    and overload that causes all the tattoos to fade away.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A tattoo can be based on any psionic power with the restrictions listed below.\r\n    All other options and specifics are determined by the creator of the tattoo, not by the one who wears and activates it.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    	 Action Time must be 9 AP or less \r\n    	 If implements include M, the material must be included in the creation \r\n    	 Implements must not include F \r\n    	 Range must be Personal or Touch \r\n    	 Target must be You or 1 creature. For target You, the tattoo recipient must be you. \r\n    	 Maximum total PP cost is 5 \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Minimum PL = Power\'s total PP cost (without PP cost reductions for supernatural affinities)\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 5 + material cost\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Scrolls \r\n     \r\n    Scrolls are spells that have been written down on paper or parchment.\r\n    The scroll also contains the power and materials required to cast the spell,\r\n    so anyone with the required affinity skill can cast the spell from a scroll without paying the cost or using any implements other than verbal.\r\n    However, casting a spell from a scroll requires the same amount of concentration as normal spellcasting, and it triggers attacks of opportunity.\r\n    Also note that reading a scroll consumes its power and turns the scroll to dust.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Any reader with the required affinity can identify the spell(s) of a scroll with a quick perusal.\r\n    Scrolls take effect when they are read out loud.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A scroll can be based on any arcane or divine spell.\r\n    The creator of the scroll chooses the action time (note that reading the scroll takes twice as long as the regular casting of the spell),\r\n    the maximum range, the duration, the maximum size of or number of targets, and any other options.\r\n    The reader can only choose the actual range and target(s) within those limits.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Reading a scroll requires an affinity for the spell skill(s) that the writer had to use to create the scroll.\r\n    In other words, the reader must have at least one skill level in a supernatural affinity skill associated with the appropriate spell skill(s).\r\n    Note, however, that the spell does not have to be known to the reader, nor does he automatically learn the spell simply by activating the scroll.\r\n    Reading from a scroll always requires a spellcasting check, with the same modifiers as a regular casting.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Minimum PL = Spell\'s total PP cost (without PP cost reductions for supernatural affinities)\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 2 + material cost\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Power Stones \r\n     \r\n    Power Stones are crystals containing a stored version of a psionic power.\r\n    The stone also contains the power and materials required to manifest the power,\r\n    so anyone with the required affinity skill can manifest the power in a power stone without paying the cost or using any implements other than verbal.\r\n    However, manifesting a power from a stone requires the same amount of concentration as normal spellcasting, and it triggers attacks of opportunity.\r\n    Also note that activating a power stone consumes its power and turns the stone to dust.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A power stone is a thumb-sized chunk of crystal.\r\n    It possesses a barely detectable interior glow if it holds a power of PL below 6.\r\n    A stone imprinted with a higher-level power glows more brightly, but never enough to provide illumination in its own right.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The power(s) stored in a stone can be identified by anyone with the required affinity simply by touching the stone.\r\n    Such a psionic user can then activate the stone by concentrating upon it and chanting.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A power stone can be based on any psionic power.\r\n    The creator of the stone chooses the action time (note that activating the stone takes twice as long as the regular manifestation of the power),\r\n    the maximum range, the duration, the maximum size of or number of targets, and any other options.\r\n    The activator can only choose the actual range and target(s) within those limits.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Activating a power stone requires an affinity for the psionic skill(s) that the creator had to use to create the stone.\r\n    In other words, the activator must have at least one skill level in a supernatural affinity skill associated with the appropriate psionic skill(s).\r\n    Note, however, that the power does not have to be known to the activator, nor does he automatically learn the power simply by activating the stone.\r\n    Activating a power stone always requires a supernatural activation check, with the same modifiers as a regular manifestation.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Minimum PL = Power\'s total PP cost (without PP cost reductions for supernatural affinities)\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 2 + material cost\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Runes \r\n     \r\n    Runes are divine spells that have been inscribed on an object or surface.\r\n    Objects of medium size or smaller can hold a single rune, while larger objects and surfaces can hold up to one rune per m 2 .\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A rune is triggered by any living creature touching it.\r\n    The only exception is the runeโs creator - he can choose whether to activate the rune or not when touching it.\r\n    Also note that only โactiveโ touching triggers a rune; attacking with a rune-inscribed weapon does not trigger the rune, for example.\r\n    When a runeโs charges have been used up, it becomes non-magical and also fades away physically.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If the rune is to be triggered by reading or by a creature passing within one square (instead of just by touch),\r\n    double the base price.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A rune can be based on most divine spells. The spell takes effect immediately when triggered, and it is always centered on the rune (range 0).\r\n    The creator of the rune chooses the duration, the maximum size of or number of targets, and any other options.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Minimum PL = Spellโs total PP cost (without PP cost reductions for supernatural affinities)\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = (Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 5 + material cost) ร (number of charges)\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Weapons \r\n     \r\n    A majority of magic weapons have no other power than providing an enhancement bonus to attack and damage,\r\n    and this is expressed as a plus bonus after the weapon name.\r\n    For example, a Longsword +4 gives an enhancement bonus of +4 to both attack and damage rolls with that weapon.\r\n    The bonus of melee weapons and thrown weapons applies to both attack and damage,\r\n    the bonus of projectile weapons applies only to attack rolls, and the bonus of ammunition applies only to damage rolls.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When enchanting a double weapon, the enchanter can choose whether to treat it as two weapons\r\n    (with separate enchantments and costs for each part of the weapon)\r\n    or as one weapon (with the same enchantments and a single cost for both parts of the weapon).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, magic ammunition is destroyed after one use (regardless of whether it hits or misses).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic weapons are sized for medium-sized wielders.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price for weapon (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 80 + cost of mundane weapon\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price for ammunition (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 2 + cost of mundane ammunition\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Shields \r\n     \r\n    A majority of magic shields have no other power than providing an enhancement bonus to parry, and this is expressed as a plus bonus after the shield name.\r\n    For example, a Large Shield +3 has a +3 enhancement to the parry bonus that the shield provides to DeC.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic shields are sized for medium-sized bearers. The type and size determines its weight.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, magic shields are masterwork quality (one encumbrance class better compared to normal shields of the same type).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 50 + cost of mundane shield\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Armor and Clothing \r\n     \r\n    A majority of magic suits of armor have no other power than providing an enhancement bonus to the armorโs DR, and this is expressed as a plus bonus after the armor name.\r\n    For example, a Scale Mail +4 has a +4 enhancement bonus to its DR.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Only one set of magic armor or clothing can be worn at a time.\r\n    If you try to combine two sets of magic armor, wear a magic robe over magic armor, or wear a magic vest under a magic robe, for example,\r\n    their magic will interfere and malfunction.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic armor and clothing are sized for medium-sized wearers,\r\n    but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n    The type and base size determine the armorโs weight.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, magic armor is masterwork quality (one encumbrance class better compared to normal armor of the same type).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 80 + cost of mundane armor\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Helmets and Hats \r\n     \r\n    Only one magic headwear can be worn per head.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic headwear are sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Goggles and Lenses \r\n     \r\n    Only one set of goggles or lenses can be worn per pair of eyes.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, lenses are created in pairs, and both of them must be worn to have the given effect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic eyewear is sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Gloves and Gauntlets \r\n     \r\n    Only one magic glove or gauntlet can be worn per hand.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, gloves and gauntlets are created in pairs, and both of them must be worn to have the given effect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic handwear are sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Boots and Shoes \r\n     \r\n    Only one magic boot or shoe can be worn per foot.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, boots and shoes are created in pairs, and both of them must be worn to have the given effect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic footwear is sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Cloaks and Mantles \r\n     \r\n    Only one magic cloak or mantle can be worn at a time.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic cloaks and mantles are sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Girdles and Belts \r\n     \r\n    Only one magic girdle or belt can be worn at a time.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic girdles and belts are sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Wands, Holy Symbols, and Dorjes \r\n     \r\n    Wands, holy symbols, and dorjes are small-sized implements that can be used as somatic components by arcane, divine, and psionic users, respectively.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A typical wand is made of wood, bone, or metal, 15 to 30 cm long and 0.5 to 1 cm thick. Some of them are tipped with a crystal or other small device.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, a wand has DeC 9, 5 HP, and DR 5.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A typical holy symbol is made of silver, gold, or similarly precious metal, and it usually has a size of 10 to 30 cm.\r\n    It can be held in one hand or carried around oneโs neck (without interfering with magic amulets and necklaces).\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, a holy symbol has DeC 7, 5 HP, and DR 5.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A typical dorje is an elongated crystal of any color, 20 to 25 cm long and about 1 cm thick.\r\n    Occasionally, a dorje is decorated with carvings or inscribed runes along a face of the crystal.\r\n    A typical dorje has DeC 7, 7 HP, and DR 8.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The maximum PL of a small implement is 10.\r\n    A typical small implement is created with a store of supernatural energy,\r\n    and this energy can be used to trigger effects related to a specific spell or power.\r\n    In order to use the implement\'s power, the wielder must have at least one skill level in an appropriate affinity skill.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 80 + cost of mundane implement\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Staves, Rods, and Psicrowns \r\n     \r\n    Staves, rods, and psicrowns are large-sized implements that can be used as somatic components by arcane, divine, and psionic users, respectively.\r\n     \r\n    A typical staff is made of wood, 1.2 to 2 m long, and 5 to 8 cm thick.\r\n    Some staffs may be constructed from bone, metal, crystal, and other exotic materials.\r\n    Many staffs are shod in metal, while others are capped by gems or arcane devices.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, a staff can be used as a quarterstaff weapon and has DeC 5, 10 HP, and DR 5.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most rods are 0.5 to 1 m long and made of metal. They can be merely decorative scepters, or they can be weapons usable as clubs or maces.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, they have DeC 6, 10 HP, and DR 10.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Some psicrowns are actually crownlike and heavily adorned, while others are simple headbands with crystal centerpieces.\r\n    Most psicrowns are metallic, but one could potentially be composed of any material. All psicrowns weigh less than 0.5 kg.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    A typical large implement is created with a store of supernatural energy,\r\n    and this energy can be used to trigger spells related to a specific supernatural skill or set of spells.\r\n    In order to use the implement\'s power, the wielder must have at least one skill level in an appropriate affinity skill.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 80 + cost of mundane implement\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Rings \r\n     \r\n    A ring must be worn on a human-like finger or claw in order to work. It will not work, for example, when worn in an ear or on a toe.\r\n    A creature can only have one active magic ring per hand (not per finger); trying to wear more causes their magical fields to interfere,\r\n    temporarily cancelling all effects of the less powerful ring.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic rings are sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Unless otherwise specified, a ring has DeC 13, DR 10, and 2 HP.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Amulets and Necklaces \r\n     \r\n    An amulet or necklace must be worn around a human-like neck in order to work.\r\n    A creature can only have one active magic necklace per neck; trying to wear more causes their magical fields to interfere and malfunction.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic necklaces are sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Magic Bracers and Bracelets \r\n     \r\n    A bracer or bracelet must be worn around a human-like forearm or wrist in order to work. It will not work, for example, when worn around a leg or ankle.\r\n    A creature can only have one active magic bracer or bracelet per arm; trying to wear more causes their magical fields to interfere and malfunction.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, bracers are created in pairs, and both of them must be worn to have the given effect.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Most magic armwear is sized for medium-sized wearers, but they will automatically adjust their size one step up or down to accommodate different wearers.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Written Works \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 200 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Musical Instruments \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Vehicles, Mounts, and Buildings \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 200 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Constructs \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = (Construct CL &times; CL + Minimum PL &times; Actual PL) &times; 200 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Other Wondrous Items \r\n     \r\n    Base price (gp) = Minimum PL &times; Actual PL &times; 100 + cost of mundane item\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Intelligent Items \r\n     \r\n    An itemโs alignment and personality can be determined randomly.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    When the interests of an intelligent item conflict with those of its owner, the item can attempt to dominate the owner.\r\n    It makes a (d20 + total PL) check against the ownerโs Will to do so. Dominance can last for up to one day at a time.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Artifacts and Relics \r\n     \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Circle Magic \r\n     \r\n    Multiple creatures with sufficient levels in Spellcraft can cooperate by joining in a circle of magic.\r\n    The leader (or the beneficiary) of the circle stands in the center, while the other participants must stand within 2 squares of the leader.\r\n    The participants do not have to be of the same class (although this is usually the case).\r\n    It is even possible for wizards, clerics, and psions to cooperate in the same circle.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The circle requires one hour for all participants to attune themselves, before the leader can receive any benefits.\r\n    A contributing participant who performs any action that requires concentration automatically leaves the circle.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    While the circle is assembled, the leader can draw PP from the other participants when he is casting spells or manifesting powers.\r\n    A participant who has the necessary skills to cast the leaderโs spell or power can also perform an โaid anotherโ action \r\n    to give the leader a spellcasting check or attack roll bonus.\r\n     \r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n		     \r\n         \r\n\r\n		\r\n         \r\n        \r\n            \r\n          \r\n		\r\n     \r\n \r\n ','2013-01-26',51.19,'d5ac11d1270fe8c607774e7a137ef146',0,2),(77,2,'http://localhost/rold20/hb06_environment.php','RoL d20 - Rules of Environment','','\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n	\r\n\r\n		\r\n	            \r\n	             \r\n	            \r\n	                 \r\n	                    RoL d20 Role-Playing System\r\n	                 \r\n	             \r\n			  \r\n		\r\n        \r\n			\r\n		 Handbook \r\n         \r\n             Introduction  \r\n             Core Mechanics  \r\n             \r\n                 Characteristics  \r\n                 Action Checks  \r\n                 Modifiers  \r\n                 Descriptors  \r\n                 Prerequisites  \r\n                 Conditions  \r\n                 Special Senses  \r\n                 Special Abilities  \r\n             \r\n             Character Generation  \r\n             \r\n                 Ability Scores  \r\n                 Character Races  \r\n                 Character Classes  \r\n                 Other Characteristics  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Combat  \r\n             \r\n                 Combat Sequence  \r\n                 Action Points  \r\n                 Combat Modifiers  \r\n                 Attack Types  \r\n                 Damage Types  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Magic  \r\n             \r\n                 Casting Spells  \r\n                 Learning Spells  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Environment  \r\n             \r\n                 Movement  \r\n                 Environment  \r\n                 The Multiverse  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Culture  \r\n             Rules of Engagement  \r\n             \r\n                 Encounters  \r\n                 Experience  \r\n                 Treasure  \r\n             \r\n             List of Skills  \r\n             \r\n                 Skill Availability  \r\n                 Skill Descriptions  \r\n             \r\n             List of Actions  \r\n             List of Spells  \r\n             List of Equipment  \r\n             \r\n	             Mundane Items  \r\n	             Complex Items  \r\n	             Item Modifications  \r\n	             Materials  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Creatures  \r\n             \r\n	             Aberrations  \r\n	             Animals  \r\n	             Monstrous Animals  \r\n	             Constructs  \r\n	             Dragons  \r\n	             Elementals  \r\n	             Humanoids  \r\n	             Monstrous Humanoids  \r\n	             Outsiders  \r\n	             Plants &amp; Fungi  \r\n	             Undead  \r\n	             Templates  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Cultures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Rules of Environment \r\n     \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Movement \r\n     Speed \r\n     \r\n    A creatureโs \r\n    adjusted speed  \r\n    indicates the number of squares it can walk per round.\r\n    Jogging is equal to two times that speed, running is equal to three times, and sprinting is equal to four times the speed.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    To convert squares per round into m/s, divide it by four. To convert it into km/h, multiply it by 1 (or 0.9, for better accuracy).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    During a typical day spent walking, a creature can cover a number of km equal to its adjusted speed times eight.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n		 \r\n    You can convert a creatureโs adjusted speed to other units, according to the following formulae:\r\n     \r\n    	\r\n    \r\n   	Speed Conversion \r\n     \r\n     Movement \r\n    sq/round \r\n    m/s \r\n    km/h \r\n    km/day \r\n   	  \r\n   	\r\n   	\r\n     Walking \r\n    Speed ร 1 \r\n    Speed ร 0.25 \r\n    Speed ร 1 \r\n    Speed ร 8 \r\n   	 \r\n   	\r\n     Jogging \r\n    Speed ร 2 \r\n    Speed ร 0.5 \r\n    Speed ร 2 \r\n    Speed ร 16 \r\n   	 \r\n   	\r\n     Running \r\n    Speed ร 3 \r\n    Speed ร 0.75 \r\n    Speed ร 3 \r\n    - \r\n   	 \r\n   	\r\n     Sprinting \r\n    Speed ร 4 \r\n    Speed ร 1 \r\n    Speed ร 4 \r\n    - \r\n   	 \r\n   	\r\n   	 \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Note that the conversion rates are somewhat simplified and not mathematically 100% accurate.\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    This table shows precalculated values for many base speeds:\r\n     \r\n    \r\n    \r\n   	Movement Rates \r\n     \r\n    \r\n    Speed \r\n    Walk \r\n    Jog \r\n    Run \r\n    Sprint \r\n   	 \r\n    \r\n    sq/r \r\n    m/s \r\n    km/h \r\n    km/day \r\n    sq/r \r\n    m/s \r\n    km/h \r\n    km/day \r\n    sq/r \r\n    m/s \r\n    km/h \r\n    sq/r \r\n    m/s \r\n    km/h \r\n   	 \r\n   	 \r\n\r\n2 2 0.5 2 16 4 1 4 32 6 1.5 6 8 2 8  3 3 0.75 3 24 6 1.5 6 48 9 2.25 9 12 3 12  4 4 1 4 32 8 2 8 64 12 3 12 16 4 16  5 5 1.25 5 40 10 2.5 10 80 15 3.75 15 20 5 20  6 6 1.5 6 48 12 3 12 96 18 4.5 18 24 6 24  7 7 1.75 7 56 14 3.5 14 112 21 5.25 21 28 7 28  8 8 2 8 64 16 4 16 128 24 6 24 32 8 32  9 9 2.25 9 72 18 4.5 18 144 27 6.75 27 36 9 36  10 10 2.5 