      Animals  \r\n	             Monstrous Animals  \r\n	             Constructs  \r\n	             Dragons  \r\n	             Elementals  \r\n	             Humanoids  \r\n	             Monstrous Humanoids  \r\n	             Outsiders  \r\n	             Plants &amp; Fungi  \r\n	             Undead  \r\n	             Templates  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Cultures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Rules of Engagement \r\n     \r\n     \r\n\r\n    Encounters \r\n     \r\n    The most common type of encounter is one that involves combat with hostile creatures,\r\n    but there is a multitude of other situations that can constitute encounters and provide the characters with experience.\r\n    Here are a few examples:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Standard combat. \r\n         Special combat, such as an arena fight or an attempt to incapacitate or capture the foe. \r\n         Traps and natural hazards. \r\n         Negotiations and role-playing challenges. \r\n         Intellectual problems and conundrums. \r\n         Moral dilemmas. \r\n         Investigation and research. \r\n     \r\n     \r\n    What is common to all reasonably challenging encounters is that they should reward the characters with XP.\r\n    The amount of XP is calculated from the encounterโs encounter level.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The DM is also free to provide additional XP for some non-encounter situations,\r\n    such as a major goal accomplished, exceptional role-playing, a brilliant idea, etc.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Random Encounters \r\n     \r\n    The 3.5E DMG and Monster Manuals have random encounter tables for cities, dungeons, and many types of wilderness environments.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Encounter Levels \r\n     \r\n    Encounter level (or EL) is a measure of how difficult a certain encounter is and is used to calculate the amount of XP awarded.\r\n    For a good but not too risky challenge, the EL should equal the average party level in a party with four characters.\r\n    For fewer than four characters, a slightly lower EL is appropriate, and vice versa.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    For combat encounters of a certain EL, an appropriate mix of creatures (based on their CLs) can be gleaned from the following table:\r\n     \r\n    	\r\n    \r\n   	Creature CL for EL \r\n     \r\n    EL \r\n    1 Creature \r\n    2 Creatures \r\n    3 Creatures \r\n    4 Creatures \r\n    6 Creatures \r\n    8 Creatures \r\n    Mixed \r\n   	  \r\n1 3 2 x 1 3 x 1/2 4 x 1/3 6 x 1/4 - 2 + 1/2  2 4 2 x 2 3 x 1 4 x 1/2 6 x 1/3 8 x 1/4 3 + 1  3 5 2 x 3 3 x 2 4 x 1 6 x 1/2 8 x 1/3 4 + 2  4 6 2 x 4 3 x 3 4 x 2 6 x 1 8 x 1/2 5 + 3  5 7 2 x 5 3 x 4 4 x 3 6 x 2 8 x 1 6 + 4  6 8 2 x 6 3 x 5 4 x 4 6 x 3 8 x 2 7 + 5  7 9 2 x 7 3 x 6 4 x 5 6 x 4 8 x 3 8 + 6  8 10 2 x 8 3 x 7 4 x 6 6 x 5 8 x 4 9 + 7  9 11 2 x 9 3 x 8 4 x 7 6 x 6 8 x 5 10 + 8  10 12 2 x 10 3 x 9 4 x 8 6 x 7 8 x 6 11 + 9  11 13 2 x 11 3 x 10 4 x 9 6 x 8 8 x 7 12 + 10  12 14 2 x 12 3 x 11 4 x 10 6 x 9 8 x 8 13 + 11  13 15 2 x 13 3 x 12 4 x 11 6 x 10 8 x 9 14 + 12  14 16 2 x 14 3 x 13 4 x 12 6 x 11 8 x 10 15 + 13  15 17 2 x 15 3 x 14 4 x 13 6 x 12 8 x 11 16 + 14  16 18 2 x 16 3 x 15 4 x 14 6 x 13 8 x 12 17 + 15  17 19 2 x 17 3 x 16 4 x 15 6 x 14 8 x 13 18 + 16  18 20 2 x 18 3 x 17 4 x 16 6 x 15 8 x 14 19 + 17  19 21 2 x 19 3 x 18 4 x 17 6 x 16 8 x 15 20 + 18  20 22 2 x 20 3 x 19 4 x 18 6 x 17 8 x 16 21 + 19  21 23 2 x 21 3 x 20 4 x 19 6 x 18 8 x 17 22 + 20  22 24 2 x 22 3 x 21 4 x 20 6 x 19 8 x 18 23 + 21  23 25 2 x 23 3 x 22 4 x 21 6 x 20 8 x 19 24 + 22  24 26 2 x 24 3 x 23 4 x 22 6 x 21 8 x 20 25 + 23  25 27 2 x 25 3 x 24 4 x 23 6 x 22 8 x 21 26 + 24  26 28 2 x 26 3 x 25 4 x 24 6 x 23 8 x 22 27 + 25  27 29 2 x 27 3 x 26 4 x 25 6 x 24 8 x 23 28 + 26  28 30 2 x 28 3 x 27 4 x 26 6 x 25 8 x 24 29 + 27  29 31 2 x 29 3 x 28 4 x 27 6 x 26 8 x 25 30 + 28  30 32 2 x 30 3 x 29 4 x 28 6 x 27 8 x 26 31 + 29       \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    Sometimes, special conditions can make an encounter more or less challenging. If that is the case, adjust EL accordingly:\r\n     \r\n	\r\n	\r\n   	EL Modifiers \r\n     \r\n     Condition \r\n    EL Mod \r\n      \r\n\r\n	\r\n	 Single hostile creature \r\n	EL = CL - 2 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 For each doubling in quantity of creatures or challenges \r\n	+2 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Difference in social class \r\n	ยฑ0.5 per rank \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Enemy in superior position \r\n	+1 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Enemy in good position \r\n	+0.5 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Enemy in poor position \r\n	-1 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Enemy has complete surprise \r\n	+1 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Enemy has partial surprise \r\n	+0.5 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Enemy is partially surprised \r\n	-0.5 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Enemy is completely surprised \r\n	-1 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Unfavorable environment \r\n	+0.5 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Bad environment \r\n	+1 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Terrible environment \r\n	+1.5 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Difficult terrain \r\n	+0.5 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	 Dangerous terrain \r\n	+1 \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	 Deadly terrain \r\n	+1.5 \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n\r\n     \r\n    Once all the modifiers have been added, round the resulting EL down to the nearest whole number.\r\n    If the EL ends up below 1, count 0 as 1/2, -1 as 1/3, -2 as 1/4, and anything lower as 0.\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n     \r\n    As you can see from the calculations above, a suitable challenge for four characters of a certain CL is\r\n    two creatures of the same CL or one creature of a CL 2 levels higher.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Awarding Experience \r\n     \r\n    If you know the EL of an encounter, then calculating the experience award is quite easy:\r\n     \r\n     \r\n         Total XP = EL ร 300. \r\n         Divide the total XP by the number of participants (on the winning side). Donโt count familiars, mounts, animal companions, and pets. Calculate only half a share for hirelings, henchmen, cohorts, etc. \r\n         Adjust the XP share for each participant based on relative level. \r\n         \r\n             For a character 3 to 5 levels above EL, halve XP. \r\n             For a character 6 or more levels above EL, award no XP. \r\n             For a character 3 or more levels below EL, award double XP. \r\n         \r\n         Adjust the XP share for each participant based on the degree of participation. A participant who falls unconscious or flees early in a combat should receive less XP than one who stays until the end. \r\n     \r\n\r\n     Experience for Work \r\n     \r\n    Even characters who do not slay monsters and loot treasures will accumulate experience over time.\r\n    During a whole lifetime, even a laborer or farmer will normally gain a couple of levels.\r\n    More dangerous and challenging work will award more experience than easy work, and more gifted individuals tend to earn more experience.\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    The following table shows how much XP you gain from typical work and\r\n    also which level a typical character would be after working the specified number of years:\r\n     \r\n\r\n    \r\n   	Work Experience \r\n     \r\n     Type of Work \r\n    XP/Day \r\n    XP/Year \r\n    Lvl (10 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (20 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (30 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (40 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (50 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (100 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (200 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (400 Yrs) \r\n    Lvl (800 Yrs) \r\n   	  \r\n Non-challenging work 1 300 3 4 4 5 6 8 11 16 22   Challenging or dangerous work 3 1000 5 6 8 9 10 14 20 28 30   Very challenging or dangerous work 8 2500 7 10 12 14 16 22 30 30 30   Very gifted individual 16 5000 10 14 17 20 22 30 30 30 30   Heroic individual 32 10000 14 20 25 28 30 30 30 30 30       \r\n \r\n\r\n    Treasure \r\n\r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    Random treasure for EL (Encounter Level):\r\n     \r\n	\r\n    \r