hin 8 sq.\r\n    Unless otherwise specified, such an item will always shed light; the owner can conceal or cover the light but not turn it off.\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Optional Advancement Rules \r\n     \r\n    The DM can adjust the rate at which the characters gain levels, if you feel that the normal rate is too fast or too slow.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Faster Advancement  (optional rule):\r\n    Multiply all XP rewards and treasures by 1.5 (or some other factor above 1).\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Slower Advancement  (optional rule):\r\n    Multiply all XP rewards and treasures by 0.5 (or some other factor below 1).\r\n     \r\n\r\n     Awarding Fate Points \r\n     \r\n    The DM should only award a new fate point when a character has done something truly exceptional.\r\n    In some cases, such as when a party of heroes has saved the lives of hundreds or thousands of innocent people,\r\n    it may even be appropriate to award one FP to each character. On average, one FP per five levels is a suitable rate of reward.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Non-Player Characters \r\n     \r\n    Non-player characters are mostly equivalent to player characters and should be generated the same way.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    Major NPCs should have 1 to 3 fate points. This not only turns them into tougher opponents but gives them a greater chance\r\n    to survive and escape an encounter that is going poorly.\r\n     \r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n		     \r\n         \r\n\r\n		\r\n         \r\n        \r\n            \r\n          \r\n		\r\n     \r\n \r\n ','2013-01-26',35.89,'7de0576c8d43cce4930ad801177ce2f1',0,2),(80,2,'http://localhost/rold20/hb09_skills.php','RoL d20 - List of Skills','','\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n	\r\n\r\n		\r\n	            \r\n	             \r\n	            \r\n	                 \r\n	                    RoL d20 Role-Playing System\r\n	                 \r\n	             \r\n			  \r\n		\r\n        \r\n			\r\n		 Handbook \r\n         \r\n             Introduction  \r\n             Core Mechanics  \r\n             \r\n                 Characteristics  \r\n                 Action Checks  \r\n                 Modifiers  \r\n                 Descriptors  \r\n                 Prerequisites  \r\n                 Conditions  \r\n                 Special Senses  \r\n                 Special Abilities  \r\n             \r\n             Character Generation  \r\n             \r\n                 Ability Scores  \r\n                 Character Races  \r\n                 Character Classes  \r\n                 Other Characteristics  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Combat  \r\n             \r\n                 Combat Sequence  \r\n                 Action Points  \r\n                 Combat Modifiers  \r\n                 Attack Types  \r\n                 Damage Types  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Magic  \r\n             \r\n                 Casting Spells  \r\n                 Learning Spells  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Environment  \r\n             \r\n                 Movement  \r\n                 Environment  \r\n                 The Multiverse  \r\n             \r\n             Rules of Culture  \r\n             Rules of Engagement  \r\n             \r\n                 Encounters  \r\n                 Experience  \r\n                 Treasure  \r\n             \r\n             List of Skills  \r\n             \r\n                 Skill Availability  \r\n                 Skill Descriptions  \r\n             \r\n             List of Actions  \r\n             List of Spells  \r\n             List of Equipment  \r\n             \r\n	             Mundane Items  \r\n	             Complex Items  \r\n	             Item Modifications  \r\n	             Materials  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Creatures  \r\n             \r\n	             Aberrations  \r\n	             Animals  \r\n	             Monstrous Animals  \r\n	             Constructs  \r\n	             Dragons  \r\n	             Elementals  \r\n	             Humanoids  \r\n	             Monstrous Humanoids  \r\n	             Outsiders  \r\n	             Plants &amp; Fungi  \r\n	             Undead  \r\n	             Templates  \r\n	         \r\n             List of Cultures  \r\n	         Index  \r\n             \r\n	             Optional Rules  \r\n	         \r\n	     \r\n		 Utilities \r\n         Administration \r\n         Other \r\n         \r\n             Analysis  \r\n             RolCalc Examples  \r\n         \r\n      \r\n		    \r\n			\r\n    Skills \r\n     \r\n    Skills cover just about everything that a creature can do and become better at, including how to climb a wall,\r\n    wield a sword, shoe a horse, cast a spell, be more perceptive, haggle with a merchant, etc.\r\n    Every time a character gains a level, he can choose to train in and improve a limited number of skills.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Skill Level \r\n     \r\n    The skill level of a skill is equal to the number of \r\n    skill points  \r\n    spent on it plus modifiers for race, culture, class, magic items, etc.\r\n    Note that ability modifiers are added to skill actions but never to the skill level itself.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Skill Benefits \r\n     \r\n    Some skills will provide specific benefits when certain skill levels are reached.\r\n    If the skill level is reduced for some reason, those benefits are lost, at least until the level returns to its higher point.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If a character has multiple skills that grant the same benefit, do not stack or double the effect. Use only the highest effect.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Skill Actions \r\n     \r\n    Many skills will have one or more associated actions.\r\n    As a characterโs skill level increases, he becomes gradually better at performing that skillโs actions.\r\n    He may also gain access to special traits and options, if such are noted in the description of the action.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    If the action has multiple associated skills, use the highest skill level for action checks but the lowest skill level\r\n    to determine access to special options.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    The success or failure of a skill action is resolved by making an \r\n    action check , \r\n    according to the rules already described.\r\n    Please refer to that chapter for details about difficulty classes, opposed skill checks, retries, taking 10, taking 20, aiding anotherโs skill use, modifiers, descriptors, etc.\r\n     \r\n     \r\n    It is worth noting that some actions have special rules for their associated skills.\r\n    For example, one skill may be used to gain access to an action, while another skill is used for the action check.\r\n    Other actions, particularly attack actions, use special modifiers (rather than the full skill) for the action check.\r\n     \r\n\r\n    Weapon Skills \r\n    \r\n	\r\n	     \r\n    In addition to the benefits listed for each weapon skill,\r\n    the following benefits and effects apply equally to all weapon skills:\r\n     \r\n\r\n	\r\n   	Weapon Skill Effects \r\n     \r\n    Skill Level \r\n     Benefit \r\n   	  \r\n\r\n	\r\n	0 \r\n	 Attacks with a weapon of this type count as improvised attacks.\r\n	If the weapon or shield has a parry bonus, halve it. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	1 \r\n	 After making an attack with the weapon, it provides no parry bonus for the rest of the round. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	3 \r\n	 You no longer lose the weapon\'s parry bonus after attacking with it.\r\n	You can switch between SP and HP damage without penalty. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	4 \r\n	 The weapon can now be used as part of a triple attack. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	8 \r\n	 The weapon can now be used as part of a quadruple attack. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	12 \r\n	 The weapon can now be used as part of a quintuple attack. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n	16 \r\n	 The weapon can now be used as part of a sextuple attack. \r\n	 \r\n   	\r\n	20 \r\n	 The weapon can now be used as part of a septuple attack. \r\n	 \r\n	\r\n     \r\n \r\n\r\n    Skill Lis